<HEAD>Tropical Storm Ernesto Fizzles En Route To Azores</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Changes overline and LEADS with 5 grafs to update with storm
fizzling, latest advisory; picks up 6th graf pvs, `The storm...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fifth tropical storm of the Atlantic hurricane
season lost its strength as it raced towards Portugal's Azores
island chain, and its remnants were absorbed by a large north
Atlantic storm system Sunday.
   Tropical Storm Ernesto, located roughly 400 miles north of the
Azores near latitude 45.0 north at longitude 28.0 west, could no
longer be identified late Sunday, according to a 10:30 p.m.
advisory from the National Hurricane Center.
   Earlier in the evening, the storm had top sustained winds of 40
mph and was racing northeastward toward the Azores at about 50 mph.
   The Civil Protection Service on the islands monitored the storm
but chose to not warn residents Sunday evening, said Azores
Regional Government spokesman Jose Manuel Baiao.
   Meteorologist Martin Nelson of the Hurricane Center said Ernesto
probably would lose strength when it moved over colder water.
   ``The storm draws its strength from the warm, moist tropical
water,'' he said. ``Even a few degrees can affect the storm.''
   Tropical storms have wind of at least 39 mph rotating around a
warm core of low pressure. If sustained wind reaches 74 mph, the
system is upgraded to a hurricane. If wind drops below 39 mph, it
is downgraded to a tropical depression.
   On Saturday, storm warnings for the Gulf coast from Cameron,
La., to Apalachicola, Fla., were canceled after a tropical
depression dissipated several hours after forming off the Texas
coast.
   The first hurricane of the season, Debby, swirled to life Friday
but was downgraded to a tropical storm hours later after moving
inland at Tuxpan, Mexico, about 165 miles northeast of Mexico City.
   The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
