<1ST_LINE>u a AM-People-Tyson 1stLd-Writethru a0848 09-04 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Tyson, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0848,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavyweight Champion Injured in Auto Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 5th graf, ``Doctors there'' to UPDATE
with statement from doctor in NYC about Tyson having ``minor trauma
to the head and the chest wall.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CATSKILL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight champion Mike Tyson suffered
what doctors called a slight head injury in an automobile accident
Sunday near his training camp.
   Tyson's car apparently skidded on a wet road about 11:20 a.m.,
said a spokesman for the boxer, Dan Klores. Tyson's car was the
only vehicle involved and the accident was not reported to
authorities, said Klores, who gave no other details.
   A state police trooper said the accident was not under
investigation. If the injuries and damage were only to Tyson and
his property, then he has 10 days to report the accident to the
state Department of Motor Vehicles, the trooper said.
   Tyson, who was recuperating from a broken bone in his right hand
suffered in a street fight two weeks ago with heavyweight Mitch
Green, was taken to a Catskill hospital and then transferred to
Columbia Green Medical Center in nearby Hudson, where he was listed
in stable condition early Sunday evening.
   Doctors there decided Tyson should have additional neurological
tests, and Tyson was transferred Sunday night to a New York City
hospital associated with Columbia University's medical school, said
Anne Grebert, a spokeswoman at the hospital in Hudson.
   Dr. Carolyn Britton, assistant professor of nuerology at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York said late Sunday,
``He suffered minor trauma to the head and the chest wall.
Currently he's in the hospital for observation and to undergo
diagnostic tests. His condition is quite stable. He's
neurologically normal.''
   He arrived in New York shortly after 9 p.m. His wife, actress
Robin Givens, was in the back of the ambulance with Tyson and tried
to put a sheet over the windows to keep camera crews from
photographing her husband.
   A few moments later, Tyson was wheeled into the hospital on a
stretcher with a sheet over his body and a towel over his face.
   As cameramen pressed forward, Givens pushed them back, shouting,
``Give him a break.''
   Tyson, whose championship bout against British champ Frank Bruno
was recently postponed until Oct. 22 because of the hand injury,
was scheduled to accompany his wife to the Soviet Union on
Wednesday.
   Green, who lost to the undefeated Tyson on May 20, 1986, in a
10-round decision, had the bridge of his nose split by Tyson in the
early-morning incident outside an all-night clothing boutique.
   Tyson claimed Green was harassing him about their meeting in the
ring. Tyson said he reacted to Green by instinct.
   In his last fight in the ring on June 27, Tyson knocked out
previously unbeaten Michael Spinks in 91 seconds, earning $22
million.
</TEXT>
