<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Watts     09-04 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Watts,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artistic Leader of Fluxus Movement Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Watts, a leader of the Fluxus Group
known for creating public art events in New York City during the
1960s, died Friday. He was 65.
   Watts died at his farm in Martins Creek after a long bout with
lung cancer, according to a longtime friend and former student,
Larry Miller. Watts was planning a solo exhibition of his recent
work at the time of his death, Miller said.
   Watts' mixed media works appeared in museums and galleries in
the United States, Canada and Europe.
   In 1946, Watts painted in the tradition of abstract
expressionism, but 12 years later, he stopped painting and began
working with a variety of media, including sculpture, film, video
and performance work.
   In the early 1960s, he was one of the artistic leaders of the
Fluxus Group, a collection of avant-garde artists whose works often
consisted of creating public events, including melting a block of
ice on a street corner. It was described by its founder, the late
George Maciunas, as ``a fusion of Spike Jones, vaudeville, gags,
children's games and Duchamp.''
   Art historian Barbara Moore of New York City said the Fluxus
Group was an important influence on the popularity of
anti-establishment forms in art of all types. The Fluxists, in
turn, were heavily influenced by the Dadaists and musician-composer
John Cage.
   At the time of his death, Watts also was developing
silk-screened works and porkchop tables with art dealer Francesco
Conz, of Verona, Italy, Miller said. In addition, Watts was working
with ``flux-med,'' silk-screened images dealing with medical
procedures, and had produced a portfolio of notes and sketches from
his work in 1964-66.
   He was an art professor at Rutgers University in New Jersey from
1953-84, and was the school's resident artist in film and mixed
media from 1964-82. Watts also taught at the Institute of Applied
Arts and Sciences in Brooklyn from 1951-52.
</TEXT>
