<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Threat     09-04 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Threat,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Man Arrested At Airport Made Threats Against Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a man who allegedly
tried to carry a gun onto an airplane and made threats against Vice
President George Bush, authorities said Saturday.
   The man, from Springfield, was being held in a psychiatric
institution and was undergoing evaluation after his arrest Friday,
police said.
   The man had not been formally charged, but was being held on
suspicion of unlawful use of a weapon. He allegedly tried to carry
a .45-caliber semiautomatic pistol through a metal detector at the
Springfield Regional Airport.
   Police said the man made threats against Bush as he was being
arrested.
   The Springfield News-Leader reported in its Sunday editions that
the man was traveling to Los Angeles, where Bush has scheduled
campaign appearances on Monday. The plane he attempted to board was
bound for Dallas, and he planned to take a connecting flight to Los
Angeles, the newspaper reported.
   Police would not comment further about the case and referred
questions to the FBI. The FBI referred questions to the Secret
Service, where a duty officer said he could not provide details
because local police handled the investigation.
</TEXT>
