<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IntellectualCruise 1stLd-Writethru a0566 09-04 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intellectual Cruise, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0566,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Stranded In Arctic Ice May Not Need Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with ship canceling call for
help. Edits to trim and to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cruise ship that became stuck in
arctic ice late last week during an educational journey for
intellectuals canceled a call for help from an icebreaker on
Saturday, the Coast Guard said.
   The Society Explorer, with 149 passengers and crew members,
reported it was in no danger because of the ice and had moved close
to Canadian waters, said John Baker, a Coast Guard spokesman in
Juneau. The ship notified Canadian maritime officials on Wednesday
it was trapped.
   ``It looks like they're free of the ice, they're moving and they
have said they no longer need assistance,'' Baker said.
   A 399-foot Coast Guard icebreaker had been en route Saturday to
assist the ship as well an oil-research support ship stranded in
ice. The research vessel, which had called for assistance Friday,
continued to await help Saturday.
   The Coast Guard had said the 236-foot ocean liner was caught in
Beaufort Sea ice 50 miles northeast of Point Barrow, or about 400
miles above the Arctic Circle.
   The liner, bound for the Northwest Passage, is operated by
Society Expeditions Cruises of Seattle, which specializes in
journeys to unconventional destinations, including Antarctica, and
emphasizes libraries and lectures.
   Some of the passengers aboard the Society Explorer have been
using the time to float in rafts routinely used for picture-taking
trips and other activities.
   ``Our entertainment on board is mostly intellectual
entertainment, not gambling and dancing,'' Peter Cox, planning
director for the cruise operator, said late last week.
   He said the ship is ``absolutely safe'' and well-stocked with
items on its continental menu.
   The cruise operator said it expects the Society Explorer to
arrive on time at its destination off the southern coast of
Newfoundland at the end of September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
