<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TankerOverturns     09-04 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Overturns,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Spill Causes Evacuation of 500; 300 from Nursing Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 people, including more than
300 from a nursing home, were evacuated Saturday after a tank truck
carrying a hazardous chemical tipped over, releasing the chemical
which formed a noxious cloud, officials said.
   No serious injuries were reported, but two men near the truck
were taken to a hospital, complaining of burning eyes and chests
after inhaling the chemical, phosphorus trichloride.
   The tanker tipped over about 6 p.m. Saturday when it sank into
the rain-soaked ground of an unpaved parking lot near U.S. Highway
78. Further details about the incident were unavailable, officials
said.
   The cloud hung over the city's north end, authorities said.
   The men were in good condition, said Trident Regional Medical
Center nursing supervisor Jan Pfennig.
   The evacuation included 15 to 20 workers of Presbyterian Home of
South Carolina and its 320 residents, some of whom were removed in
stretchers.
   Evacuees were taken to Summerville Elementary School and the
South Carolina Marine and Wildlife Resources Coastal Center, about
six miles away.
   Authorities said they didn't know how much of the chemical had
leaked out.
   Phosphorus trichloride is a clear, colorless, fuming liquid used
chiefly in organic synthesis as a chlorinating agent.
   When it comes in contact with moisture, it forms a compound
similar to an acid, according to Dr. Bruce Metts, director of the
Palmetto Poison Center in Columbia. It can irritate the eyes and
the mucous membranes of the respiratory system, Metts said.
</TEXT>
