<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0657,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Depression Fizzles In Gulf; Tropical Storm Brews In
Atlantic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Changes overline and UPDATES throughout with tropical
depression dissipating, tropical storm warnings discontinued. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly formed tropical depression dissipated
several hours after it sprang from an area of disturbed weather off
the Texas coast as a tropical storm churned in the Atlantic,
forecasters said Saturday.
   An Air Force aircraft was unable to identify any center of
circulation with the depression and all warnings along the Gulf
coast were discontinued.
   Meantime, a depression in the Atlantic some 800 miles northeast
of Bermuda became Tropical Storm Ernesto, according to a 6 p.m. EDT
advisory issued by the National Hurricane Center. The storm was
moving north-northeast.
   Tropical storm warnings issued at 5 p.m. CDT Saturday from
Cameron, La., to Apalachicola were discontinued by late evening,
according to an advisory from the National Hurricane Center.
   The Atlantic storm was moving at 30 mph, and mainly posed a
concern at sea, hurricane specialist Bob Case said. Gradual
strengthening was expected over the next 24 hours.
   ``It appears it is going to get some help with the colder air
temperatures north of it ... and just become a big storm in the
Atlantic,'' he said.
   Depressions are upgraded to tropical storms when their maximum
sustained winds reach 39 mph. Hurricanes pack winds of at least 74
mph.
   The first hurricane of the season, Debby, was downgraded Friday
to a tropical storm after moving inland at Tuxpan, Mexico, about
165 miles northeast of Mexico City.
   The hurricane season runs June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
