<HEAD>Four Dead in Grand Canyon Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new details of crash; where victims
were from. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GRAND CANYON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four men died Saturday night when
their single-engine plane crashed while taking off from Grand
Canyon Airport, officials said.
   The Cessna 172 stalled shortly after takeoff and the aircraft
spun out of control, crashing about 100 yards north of the runway,
said Ron Warren, a spokesman for Grand Canyon Airlines, which is
based at the airport. There were no survivors.
   The plane had to abort its first takeoff attempt because it had
taken on too much fuel, said Chuck Daehler, who is with Grand
Canyon Helicopters.
   The initial attempt was at 6:20 p.m, Warren said. The pilot
radioed the control tower that there was too much fuel on board and
then returned to the airport, he said.
   ``They tried to spend the night, but everything in town was
full,'' Warren said.
   The plane then made a second attempt after draining the excess
fuel but the plane crashed just after 9 p.m., Daehler said. The
airport runway is about 10 miles south of the canyon's south rim.
   The victims were all men in their mid-20s from Rustin, La.,
Warren said. Their identities were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
