<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Bangladesh-Floods     09-04 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bangladesh-Floods,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Million People Marooned, 40 More Die In Floods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsoon floods have marooned an
estimated 20 million people across Bangladesh, officials said
Sunday. Forty more people died in the deluge, bringing the death
toll to 882, a newspaper reported.
   ``Shortage of medicine, cooked food and drinking water is
causing untold miseries to millions of marooned people,'' said an
official at the Relief Ministry in Dhaka.
   Rains battered Dhaka on Sunday, where an estimated 500,000
people have taken shelter from adjoining low-lying areas. Their
presence and uncertainities over the floods caused prices of goods
to rise in the city. Prices for rice, a staple, have risen 40
percent.
   The capital remained cut off for the third day Sunday as more
areas of the runways at the international airport were submerged.
   Relief officials were unable to reach many interior areas where
people were feared trapped with meager or no food and potable
water, officials from four areas told The Associated Press by
telephone. The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They estimated that 20 million people were marooned in 50 of the
country's 64 districts that were battered by the floods.
   The government issued new appeals for boats, helicopters and 3
million tons of food to combat the deluge.
   The Sangbad newspaper said 40 people died across the country on
Saturday, taking the total death toll in the current monsson floods
that began in June to at least 882. The government toll, considered
understated, stood at 300.
   In Dhaka, several gas stations closed their pumps and hung ``No
Gas'' signs.
   ``Unless to get fresh supplies the pumps will remain closed,''
said one station owner, Giasuddin Ahmed.
   Annual floods are common in Bangladesh, one of the poorest
countries in the world. At least 1,500 people died in floods last
year. In 1985, more than 10,000 people were killed when cyclones
and tidal waves hit low islands in the Bay of Bengal, about 130
miles south of Dhaka.
</TEXT>
