<2ND_LINE>BC-Hostage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0702,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Policeman Releases Hostage After 15-Hour Ordeal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES overline to reflect hostage released.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-policeman convicted of participating in a
pension fund scandal ended a 15-hour hostage ordeal by releasing
the man who had exposed the scam, police said.
   Anthony D. Daniele, 39, remained on the 15th floor of the office
building where he had held John Frank, vice president of the city
police board, said police spokeswoman Linda Hancock.
   Daniele, who was armed with an unidentified weapon, had held no
other hostages. He let Frank go about 1:30 a.m. Sunday. Frank
apparently was unharmed, police said.
   A hostage-response team and dozens of officers who had
surrounded the building continued to negotiate with Daniele through
the early morning hours, Hancock said.
   ``Right now they're still talking with him about the possibility
of his coming out and ending the whole thing,'' she said.
   ``We're just talking,'' said Lt. Col. Calzona Hall at an earlier
briefing as the ordeal passed the 12-hour mark. ``He's been very
cooperative.''
   The incident began at 10:30 a.m.
   Hancock said Daniele earlier had demanded to make a statement
over St. Louis radio station KMOX-AM.
   Besides an eight-year term, Daniele was ordered to make
restitution of $200,000.
   Frank, a lawyer and a member of the appointed civilian board
that administers the Police Department, exposed the kickback
scandal that cost police and fire pension funds an estimated
$333,000.
   The scam was carried out by paying a brokerage artificially high
commissions on stock transactions that were made with pension
funds, prosecutors said. Participants in the scheme were then given
back part of the money.
   Daniele, who headed the police pension fund, was the only one of
six men indicted in the scam to stand trial. He was convicted of
charges that included extortion, conspiracy and mail fraud, and
could have received as much as 32 years in prison.
</TEXT>
