<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Britain-Warship 1stLd-Writethru   09-04 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Warship, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0699,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE London</HEAD>
<HEAD>11 Injured After British Destroyer, Container Ship Collide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with destroyer sailing to port,
destination of container ship, details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British container ship and a British
destroyer accompanying it toward the Persian Gulf collided, poking
a hole in the warship and injuring 11 of its crewmen, officials
said.
   British naval sources in Oman said the accident occurred
Saturday night when the HMS Southampton and the British-registered
Tor Bay were 15 miles off the United Arab Emirates port of Fujairah
on the Gulf of Oman.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonoymity, said the
Southampton sailed on to Fujairah after a brief stop to assess its
damage. During that stop, the 4,000-ton ship appeared ``badly
holed'' and was ``seriously flooding,'' they said.
   But the sources said the situation was under control.
   The 34,477-ton Tor Bay, which was on its way from Singapore to
Dubai, in the United Arab Emirates, escaped with only minor damage
to its bow and continued its voyage after the accident. Its owners,
P and O of London, said it would be repaired at Dubai.
   The Defense Ministry in London said 11 crewmen were injured _
three of them with broken bones, one suffering shock and the other
seven with minor cuts and bruises.
   On arrival at Fujairah, the sailors with broken bones were moved
to the local government hospital. One witness at the port said the
Southampton was ``damaged extensively. ... (there's) a big gash on
its port side, bigger than the size of a car.''
   The Southampton has a 253-man crew. It came to the Persian Gulf
region to join the Royal Navy patrolling units last month.
   The sources said they could not tell how the collision occurred,
especially that warships usually sail at least one mile away from
the vessels they are escorting in the gulf.
   The Southampton is one of two Royal Navy destroyers and a
frigate that accompany merchant ships into and out of the gulf
because of the 8-year-old Iraq-Iran conflict. There also are three
British mine sweepers and three support vessels, including the Olna
and Diligence, the sources added.
   A cease-fire began in the Iraq-Iran war Aug. 20.
</TEXT>
