<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Attacked As They Defuse 300-Pound Bomb In Northern
Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young men on Sunday hurled
gasoline and acid bombs at British soldiers as they tried to defuse
a 300-pound bomb, but police drove off the assailants and the job
was completed safely.
   Two men were detained for questioning, and a police officer
received medical treatment after ammonia was thrown into his eyes,
said a spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's
police force.
   The confrontation occurred in the mainly Roman Catholic New
Lodge area of north Belfast, where authorities found the bomb in a
parked, stolen car along with several other detonators and timing
devices. Sixty homes in the area were evacuated until the bomb was
defused about 6 a.m.
   Police fired plastic bullets at the young men who attempted to
disrupt the work of the bomb disposal experts by throwing ``petrol
bombs, acids bombs and other assorted missiles,'' said the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for planting the bomb,
but the police spokesman said there was ``a rather strong
possibility'' it was the work of the outlawed Irish Republican Army.
   The IRA is fighting a guerrilla war to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the mostly Protestant province with the
mainly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
