<HEAD>Soviet Boat Visits South Korean For First Time Since 1945</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since Korea was
divided in 1945, a Soviet vessel docked Sunday at a South Korean
port.
   A Soviet tourist ship, the 12,798-ton Mikhail Sholokhov, arrived
at the western port city of Inchon, 25 miles west of Seoul. The
ship went to Inchon after stopping at the southern port of Pusan on
Saturday.
   In Pusan, the venue for yachting competition in the Olympics,
the ship dropped off a 27-member Soviet yachting delegation and 56
tourists.
   The Soviet vessel will remain in Inchon until the end of the
Games, held from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2.
   The last visit of a Soviet vessel occurred in 1945, when U.S.
and Soviet troops facilitated the surrender of Japan, which
colonized the peninsula for 36 years. Seoul has no diplomatic
relations with Moscow, which backed North Korea during the
1950-1953 Korean War.
