<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FreighterChase     09-04 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freighter Chase,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freighter Surrenders In Britain After Outrunning French
Authorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo ship suspected of carrying drugs
surrendered to British customs officials after it was chased across
the English Channel by French authorities who fired warning shots
when it refused to stop.
   A British customs spokesman identified the vessel as the
Honduras-registered Salton Sea and said it failed to stop for a
routine check by French customs officials off Boulogne on the
northeast French coast late Saturday.
   ``The French fired two shots across her bows and she then did a
bunk (steamed away) into British waters,'' said the spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   After a chase 40 miles across the English Channel, the freighter
surrendered to the unarmed British coast guard cutter Swift and was
escorted into Ramsgate on the southeast coast of England.
   Customs officers, specially trained dogs and divers were
searching the vessel Sunday. British news reports said the ship was
thought to be carrying illegal drugs, but the Customs and Excise
Department would not comment.
   Bruce Davies, an assistant collector for the Customs and Excise
Department, said no further information would be disclosed about
the ship until it was fully searched, a job that was not expected
to be completed Sunday.
   ``It is a pretty big ship and it is going to take a lot of
rummaging,'' Davies said. ``It is a long hard job and we will be at
it for some while.''
   Kent County Constabulary in Ramsgate said two men were taken off
the ship and held in the town's police cells before being
transferred Sunday to the police station in nearby Dover.
   About 30 British customs officers, some carrying bolt cutters
and electronic equipment, boarded the ship, accompanied by two dogs
trained to sniff for illegal drugs. Two divers disappeared under
the ship, anchored 50 yards from the outer harbor wall.
   The British cutter and the French clipper Vent D'Avac, which
fired the warning shots, were docked nearby.
   The spokesman said he did not know the freighter's destination,
but he said it had come from South America.
   The Salton Sea is not listed in Lloyd's Register of Ships. But
Press Association, the domestic British news agency, said the vague
outline of ``Salton Seahorse, Virgo City, La.'' could be seen on
the ship.
   A ship called the Salton Seahorse is listed in Lloyd's as being
owned by Seahorse Fleet Inc. of Morgan City, La. That ship, built
in 1973 by the American Marine Corp. of New Orleans, is a
170-foot-long supply ship.
</TEXT>
