<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RedOnion     09-04 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Red Onion,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant Chain Settles Discrimination Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A southern California chain of
restaurants will pay $15,000 each to 23 people who sued, alleging
were denied service because of race or ethnicity.
   Friday's settlement is the third involving the Red Onion chain
of Mexican food restaurants, based in the Los Angeles suburb of
Carson. It was accused of using dress codes and other excuses to
bar minorities from their dining rooms.
   Russell Kerr, who represented black, Hispanic and Arab
plaintiffs, said four more people were expected to accept the
settlements this week.
   In depositions, Red Onion employees said board president Ronald
Newman used the code name ``Norwegians'' for minorities and would
say: ``The room is too dark. There's too many Norwegians in here,''
Kerr said.
   Newman denied the allegations, and Red Onion attorney William A.
Kurlander said that he was unaware of any corporate policy of
discrimination but that he could not speak for each of the chain's
14 restaurants.
   ``I'm not interested in the money, but I'm interested in the
principle,'' said Walter Lujan, 30, who claimed he was denied entry
to the Santa Ana Red Onion in 1986.
   ``Orange County is such a conservative, white type of county.
There was an opportunity to set a precedent here in Orange County
of how things must change.''
   In November, six Iranians who sued in Los Angeles received a
$240,000 settlement and an apology. In addition, at least 22 people
who complained of discrimination in 1986 accepted $500 payments and
agreed to forego legal action.
   The first complaints in 1986 prompted the state to suspend
liquor licenses for six months at Red Onions in Santa Ana,
Fullerton, Riverside and Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
