<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     09-04 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll from Starvation Hits 8,000 In Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting and seasonal flooding are
blocking Western relief efforts in southern Sudan, where local
reports indicate 8,000 people have starved to death in recent
weeks, authorities say.
   Southerners arriving from Wau, 660 miles south of Khartoum, said
Saturday that thousands of people trekking north toward the
Kordofan region have been marooned by floods for days. Many died,
they said.
   ``Dozens of people have fallen dead on the roads leading to
Meriam camp due to hunger,'' one new arrival told The Associated
Press.
   Meriam is 500 miles south of Khartoum. The Rev. Aengus Finucane,
director of the Irish aid agency CONCERN, said last month that
about 40 people were dying there daily.
   Bakheet Hussein, another recent arrival, said he knew that
thousands of people ``trying to flee the town of Wau to Babanusa
have perished before reaching there.'' Babanusa is 250 miles north
of Wau.
   A government official said last week that at least 4,000 people
died in Aweil, a way station between Wau and Babanusa that has been
under siege by rebel forces for almost a year.
   Reports from the south reaching the Council of the South, a
government body, said the death toll in Aweil alone rose to 8,000
in recent days and that starvation and disease threatened thousands
in other southern towns.
   Outside confirmation of the reports was virtually impossible.
Even without the chaos caused by August's floods, travel in the
south by journalists and most outsiders has been restricted for
years because of the civil war.
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Organization took up arms
against the government in 1983 and claims control over 90 percent
of the southern countryside and towns.
   Fierce fighting between the government and rebels has forced
southerners to leave crops and cattle for the safety of towns.
Faced with dwindling food and medical supplies in these towns,
southerners often try to make their way farther north, usually on
foot.
   Another report reaching the Council of the South said the
situation in Aweil ``is dramatically deteriorating.'' It said
floods washed away roads and bridges connecting the town with the
outside, blocking whatever relief supplies might get through.
   The report said food supplies, especially southern Sudan's
staple sorghum, are low in Wau and Juba, the south's main city 750
miles south of Khartoum.
   The report said floods caused by heavy rains and fighting in the
area was obstructing Western relief organizations' efforts to bring
food and medicine to these areas.
</TEXT>
