<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Non-Aligned     09-04 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates Gather For Non-Aligned Meeting Amid Security Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears of a terrorist attack prompted
strict security measures Sunday as senior government officials from
95 countries began gathering for the Non-Aligned Movement's foreign
ministers conference.
   The five-day conference opens Monday with preparatory meetings.
President George Vassilou formally begins the three-day foreign
ministers' session Wednesday.
   Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat is
expected to attend the conference in his current campaign to muster
support for a plan to proclaim a provisional government for an
independent Palestinian state.
   The conference will map out the 101-member Non-Aligned
Movement's role over the next decade and decide its next chairman.
Zimbabwe is the current chairman.
   Conservative members are backing Indonesia, while more radical
states support Nicaragua, the only other official candidate.
   Some speculated that Cyprus could step in as a compromise
candidate to break any deadlock that develops.
   A special anti-terrorist squad and about 1,500 police officers
have been mobilized to guard the newly built conference center on
Nicosia's southern outskirts and the 14 hotels where the delegates
will stay.
   Police in the Greek-controlled sector of the war-divided east
Mediterranean island have carried out mock terrorist attacks over
the last few days to test security.
   Mobile patrols have been stepped up between Larnaca airport, on
the coast south of the capital, and the port city of Limassol.
   Police units have combed the ravines and hills bordering the
highway. Armored vehicles have been deployed around the beachside
airport.
   Cyprus government spokesman Akis Fantis said peace moves in the
Iran-Iraq war, Angola, the Algeria-Morocco Sahara dispute, the
Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan and U.S.-Soviet relations were
``of tremendous importance'' to the movement.
   Fighting between Iran and Iraq, both members of the movement,
halted Aug. 20 when a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect.
   With the recent rapprochement between Greece and Turkey, Greek
and Turkish Cypriots are trying to reconcile their differences as
well.
   Cyprus has been divided since the Turkish Army invaded in July
1974 and seized the northern third of the island.
   Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, and Rauf Denktash, leader
of the Turkish Cypriot minority, broke a four-year deadlock when
they met in Geneva under United Nations auspices Aug. 24.
</TEXT>
