<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignKickoff Bjt   09-04 0973</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Kickoff, Bjt,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Game Well Under Way at Labor Day Kickoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis make
campaign-launching Labor Day appearances Monday in a race for the
presidency that has ignored the ceremonial starting point and is
already a close and caustic contest.
   ``It kicked off earlier than any presidential campaign I've ever
seen,'' said Frank Greer, a consultant to Democratic candidates.
``The intensity this early is really astounding.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic nominee who has seen a huge midsummer's
lead evaporate, campaigns through the industrial Northeast and
Midwest hungering for the elusive intangibles of momentum and
initiative that he once commanded.
   Bush, the vice president and Republican nominee, enters the
final nine weeks of his race for the White House appearing in
control of their long-distance debate, at least for now, and
enjoying a resurrection in the polls. He was campaigning on the
West Coast.
   Dukakis communications director Leslie Dach said Labor Day is
``when the season really starts'' and represents the point where
the Massachusetts governor steps up his pace from three days of
campaign travel to five each week.
   But the Bush campaign was making no effort to cloak its
candidate in the traditions of Labor Day. Bush passed up a chance
for a visual send-off before the Statue of Liberty, where Ronald
Reagan began his fall campaign in 1980, and a symbolic appearance
with his running mate.
   ``Labor Day as an opening day has been overtaken by events,''
said Bush spokesman Mark Goodin.
   Those events include a blistering round of attacks on Dukakis
leveled by Bush immediately after the Democrats spent four July
days ridiculing the vice president at their Atlanta convention.
And, they include the debate over Bush's controversial running
mate, Dan Quayle, whose selection at a minimum forced a vacationing
electorate to notice this presidential race.
   Both campaigns have revealed their themes, too. Dukakis is
focusing on the economy, and middle class unease about the economic
future, as well as questioning the judgment and fitness of the
Republican ticket.
   ``Most Americans don't feel they're sharing in George Bush's
prosperity,'' said Dach, the Dukakis spokesman. ``We're going to
run on the economic issues. Those are the issues that are going to
decide this election. What Bush is trying to do is deflect the
debate off the issues that people really care about.''
   Bush has concentrated on raising doubts about Dukakis and his
record as governor, while suggesting gentle change from the Reagan
administration in such areas as protecting the environment. Now
Bush plans to focus on jobs and the economy.
   Still to come are what may be the main events: televised
debates, where an error can wreck a candidacy; and the wars of
television advertising, which are certain to be hard fought.
   Bush's TV ads will begin airing soon, campaign manager Lee
Atwater said. Media adviser Roger Ailes is not tipping his hand on
the content, but campaign sources said among them may be one
featuring Maryland victims terrorized by convicted murderer Willie
Horton, who escaped while on a furlough from the Massachusetts
prison system.
   Bush has made a major campaign issue of the furlough program
that allowed passes for first-degree murderers, and which Dukakis
reluctantly agreed to amend in the face of public outcry.
   Confident of his debating style honed as a public television
show host, Dukakis is eager to confront Bush. The Bush campaign,
however, has attempted to minimize the debates. It has agreed to
two debates, plus a third between the running mates, and is
insisting on scheduling them in late September and early October _
when the Olympics and World Series may keep some viewers away.
   Dukakis responded strongly to Bush during their summer jousting,
even at one point evoking the imagery of rotting fish heads in
describing President Reagan and his vice president.
   But his campaign clearly is frustrated by the appearance that he
is reacting and on the defensive, unable to direct the debate.
   There was implicit admission that all is not well in Dukakis'
announcement Friday of the return of his former campaign manager
John Sasso, who resigned in controversy a year earlier.
   And Dukakis on occasion has seemed tentative and reluctant in
their long-distance debates, some believe.
   ``I'm not sure the Democrats have given back as good as we
got,'' said Greer. ``I think we were lulled by that large lead.''
   Where he once led by double-digit margins, Dukakis was shown in
a dead heat with Bush according to most recent polls, including an
ABC News-Washington Post poll last week. It had Dukakis up by 1
percentage point, 43-42, statistically insignificant.
   ``I don't think anyone in the campaign, from top to bottom,
anticipated the race tightening up to our advantage this quick,''
said Bush manager Atwater. ``Our key is not to get confident, not
to get cocky about it.''
   Some Republicans believe Bush still trails a bit, however. ``I
would say we're still realistically 5-6-7 points down,'' said
Republican consultant Eddie Mahe, who is doing work for the Bush
campaign on the West Coast.
   He bases that on the difference, in some polls, of respondents
who say they are deeply committed to a candidate.
   The battle is largely for those wavering or swing voters. They
are often described as Reagan Democrats, self-identified
independents or Democrats who turned away from the party in 1980
and 1984.
   But what is striking is that the race is breathtakingly close
all across the nation _ including the big battleground states like
California, Ohio, Michigan and Texas. Even Dukakis's home state of
Massachusetts is even or nearly so in a recent poll.
   ``When Dukakis was ahead, he was ahead everywhere. When Bush
took the lead, it was everywhere. When it evens out now, it's kind
of even everywhere,'' said Greer. ``It's amazing.''
</TEXT>
