<HEAD>Brazil Postpones New Constitution to Prepare Celebration</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government postponed the enactment
of a new constitution until next month to have more time to prepare
festivities to accompany the event.
   House Speaker Ulysses Guimaraes had suggested Sept. 23 to
coincide with the first days of spring in the Southern Hemisphere,
but other congressmen said more time was need to get the
celebration ready.
   Guimaraes said Saturday that the new date was Oct. 5.
   Rep. Marcelo Cordeiro told reporters that legislators were
considering setting up a big podium outside the Congress, with pop
music stars, regional dances and nationwide TV coverage.
   The 559-member, two-chamber legislature finished work Friday on
the new constitution, Brazil's eighth. It will replace the
authoritarian charter handed down two decades ago by the military
government that ruled Brazil from 1964 to 1985.
   The 245-article constitution took 19 months to prepare and
touches nearly every aspect of Brazilian life, from maternity leave
and land reform to labor strikes and interest rates.
   Congress is to approve the final draft Sept. 22.
