<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss Italy,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contestants Say New Miss Italy Is Too Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALSOMAGGIORE TERME, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Miss Italy, the first
popularly elected winner of the annual beauty pageant, was hooted
by some fellow contestants because she is 10 years older than many
of them.
   Nadia Bengala, who says she is 26, was crowned Saturday night
during the first live television broadcast of the contest by the
state-run RAI network.
   ``I am very happy, especially after all the controvery over my
age,'' she said, drawing cries of protest from some of the other 63
contestants.
   ``They are very beautiful,'' she added, ``but they can be even
more beautiful in 10 years.'' The runner-up is 17 and third-place
finisher 16.
   Another contestant was disqualified when it was revealed she was
14. After rushing off the stage in tears, she was awarded the title
``Miss Mascot.''
   Last year's Miss Italy pageant was also marred by controversy.
The winner was stripped of her title when she admitted that she was
married and a mother.
   Miss Bengala is a beauty contest veteran who won the Lady Italy
title in 1983. Because she had no official document to prove her
age _ she said her passport was stolen at the Milan train station _
Italian newspapers and news agencies suggested she could be older
than 26.
   Miss Bengala, a part-time model who lives in Milan, received
141,756 votes from television viewers who called a central number.
The call-in votes were combined with those of the on-site jury.
Miss Bengala was the first choice of the TV viewers, but only the
third pick of the jurors.
