<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FishKill 1stLd-Writethru a0730 09-04 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Kill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0730,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Claims Trout In Pristine Sierra River</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first graf to insert dropped word `self-sustaining.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The release of silty water from the
bottom of a reservoir to irrigate alfalfa has killed hundreds of
fish in one of the last self-sustaining trout streams in the West,
authorities said.
   The release turned a nine-mile stretch of the once-pristine East
Walker River in the eastern Sierra Nevada into a silt-choked brown
wash.
   Some of the trout asphyxiated when silt clogged their gills were
almost 2 feet long and weighed more than 9 pounds.
   The river was declared dead by California Trout, a 3,400-member
sportsmen's conservation group that opposed the water release.
   ``The reservoir release has successfully killed all the trout''
in the river, said spokesman Rick Rockel, who called the loss
``catastrophic.''
   The water _ the lower 12 feet of the Bridgeport Reservoir _ was
released on Wednesday and Thursday for farmers and ranchers
downstream near Yerington, Nev.
   Farmers and ranchers said they needed the water and had a legal
right to it. They said they're struggling after two straight dry
winters and that the water might save this year's crop of alfalfa,
used as livestock feed.
   The East Walker, 110 miles south of Reno, Nev., was one of the
eastern Sierra's last trophy trout streams. It did not need to be
stocked, having one of the few self-sustaining wild trout
populations in the West.
   ``All these dead fish, it sends a chill up my spine,'' said Mike
Markwith, a fly fisherman from Redwood City. ``We'll find some
place else to fish this weekend, but it won't be as good.''
   In August, California Trout unsuccessfully tried to obtain a
restraining order against the draining of the reservoir.
   ``We have no problems sharing this water with our neighbors in
Nevada _ they have a problem, too,'' Rockel said. ``But we have a
problem of losing our fishery and it looks like we did, all because
of improper management.''
</TEXT>
