<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BassoonFound     09-04 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bassoon Found,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Musician's $15,000 Bassoon Was Sold for $3 and Pack of Cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shopkeeper who bought a stolen, $15,000
bassoon for $3 and a pack of cigarettes tracked down the owner,
who's once again playing a cheerful tune.
   ``I thought it was shark bait by this time. I was very fearful
it would end up in a dumpster or the river,'' Cyrus Segal, 62, a
bassoonist with the New York City Opera, said Saturday.
   When he finally sat down with the 5-foot-long woodwind again,
Segal said, ``I felt like I was having a conversation with a
long-lost friend.''
   Mark Mavris, owner of a luggage and gift shop, said he had been
looking for the bassoon's rightful owner since an apparently
homeless man sold it to him.
   ``He said he wanted $10 for it _ he didn't know what it was,''
Mavris said. ``I gave him $3. I guess he figured he could get lunch
money out of it.''
   Segal was standing outside Lincoln Center on Wednesday, the
instrument in a black canvas bag wedged between his leg and a
building column, when it was snatched, police said.
   His wife, Myra, who is also a musician, said a colleague called
her and told her Mavris was looking for the bassoon's owner.
   ``He's been stopping musicians on the street and asking them,''
she said. ``I ran out, ran down the street and the man would not
even take the three dollars for it.''
   Segal has owned the double-reed bass woodwind for 25 years. It
was made by Heckel, a German company that takes three years to fill
an order for an instrument.
</TEXT>
