<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BendedKnee     09-04 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bended Knee,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McFarlane Sees Parallels: U.S. Policies in Vietnam and Central
America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane finds ``very legitimate''
parallels between U.S. involvement in Vietnam and Reagan
administration policy in Central America, according to a new book
in which he is quoted.
   The book, ``On Bended Knee: The Press and the Reagan
Presidency,'' also quotes Michael Deaver, former deputy White House
chief of staff, as saying that Alexander Haig ``wanted to clean
house'' in Central America and made ``outrageous'' statements about
the subject when he was secretary of state.
   The book was written by Mark Hertsgaard, an investigative
journalist who has written two books about the nuclear power
industry. It is being published this month by Farrar, Straus &
Giroux.
   Hertsgaard argues in the book that the news media have shown a
``more deferential attitude'' toward President Reagan than toward
other recent presidents.
   This made it easy, he says, for Haig ``to promote his analysis
of the situation in Central America through the press'' _ an
analysis that held that the Soviet Union and Cuba were fomenting
revolution in the region.
   As controversy developed over the administration's Central
American policies, however, Hertsgaard writes, ``a new theme
emerged in news coverage: Was the United States getting involved in
another Vietnam?''
   Reagan repeatedly denied that he intended to send U.S. troops to
the region and ``seemed almost to resent the Vietnam parallels,''
Hertsgaard said.
   The author reports, however, that McFarlane, in an interview for
the book, said the issues of Cuban-Soviet involvement and of a
possible repeat of Vietnam ``contribute to a very reasonable
framework for press treatment of the issue.''
   ``Evoking a recollection of Vietnam is a very legitimate point
to make, because it simply exposes the reality of difficulty you
will have in sustaining popular support for your policy,''
McFarlane is quoted as saying. ``That's a valid criticism. You may
not like it, but it's real.''
   McFarlane has pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of
withholding information from congressional committees investigating
covert aid to Nicaraguan rebels at a time when military assistance
to them was prohibited.
   Hertsgaard reports that both Deaver and his boss, then White
House Chief of Staff James Baker, were ``leery of the Central
America initiative from the start.''
   ``Baker and I tried constantly to keep under control the whole
Central America thing,'' Deaver is quoted as saying. ``Haig wanted
to go in there and clean house. I can't even tell you what things
he said; things that were outrageous. And I remember him saying, in
his inimitable style, `Mr. President, this is one you can win!'
talking about Nicaragua.''
   ``This was five years ago: This is one you can win and you can
win it quickly,'' Deaver is quoted as saying in the November 1986
interview, continuing to recall Haig's words.
   ``Baker and I constantly cautioned the president about that,''
Deaver said. ``A, you cannot win. B, the American people will not
stand still for a war in Central America.''
   Hertsgaard said Haig declined to be interviewed for the book.
   McFarlane told the writer, ``Al wanted a major stress (and) the
use of Reagan's high political standing early in his first term.
(The) president didn't want to do that. He wanted to invest that
capital in tax reduction.''
   Hertsgaard reports that the three major television networks
broadcast 186 news stories about El Salvador in the first three
months of 1981. However, he says, after a White House decision to
``low-key'' the issue, the number dropped to 60 in the following
three months although the civil war in the Central American country
continued unabated.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: W. Dale Nelson covers the White House for The Associated
Press and is currently in California where President Reagan
vacationing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
