<HEAD>East German Border Troops Thwart Escape Attempt But Two Others
Flee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two East Germans escaped to the West by swimming
across a canal Sunday, but border guards thwarted another escape
attempt when they fired at a man trying to flee his communist
homeland, police said.
   The would-be escapist, who did not appear to be injured, was
arrested and led away by border troops, a police spokesman in West
Berlin said.
   In all, two East German border guards and four other people have
fled to West Berlin the last three days.
   Police said two men in their early 30s swam across a canal to
reach West Berlin early Sunday.
   On Saturday, the two guards jumped across the heavily fortified
border into the British-controlled sector of West Berlin, police
said. Both guards were being questioned by British authorities,
police said.
   On Friday, two men made a daring pre-dawn escape to West Berlin
by swimming across the Havel River. The men were spotted by an East
German patrol boat that gave pursuit to the border but no shots
were fired.
   None of the escapees was identified in accordance with West
German regulations.
