<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Forum     09-04 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Forum,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Approves Movement Advocating Multiparty Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist government has approved a
new group that advocates multiparty elections, but members say they
have no intention of starting their own political party.
   The Hungarian Democratic Forum established itself as a
``democratic, intellectual and political movement'' by adopting a
charter on Saturday, the state news agency MTI reported.
   Hungarian state radio said the forum wants to field candidates
for national, regional and local elections.
   But forum members said they don't plan to form a political party
and only want to promote ``an open coalition-type movement, open to
any honest thoughts and initiatives.''
   The forum's 364 delegates met in a tent at Lakitelek, 75 miles
south of Budapest, the same village where a group of nonconformist
intellectuals met in September 1987 to form a loose organization
under the same name.
   Commenting on the forum meeting, government spokesman Gyoergy
Marosan told Hungarian radio, ``On the basis of government policy,
this is a welcome development.''
   Marosan, the son of a former leading Social Democrat in
pre-communist Hungary, said the government would cooperate with the
movement as long as the forum cooperates.
   He said if people wonder about the ``foundation of a new
party,'' they underestimate recent changes in Hungary.
   Prime Minister Karoly Grosz, who took over from Janos Kadar in
May, has pushed for political and economic reforms. Kadar had led
Hungary since Soviet troops put down the Hungarian uprising in 1956.
   The fact that the meeting was reported in the state media was
another indication that the forum has received official blessing.
   MTI said the forum considers a multiparty system ``indispensable
in the process of democracy.''
   The news agency quoted forum leaders as saying the movement
wants to operate ``within the framework of constitutionality and
legality, before the general public in all openness.''
   One of the speakers at the meeting, Csaba G. Kis, called for a
coalition of socialists, Christian Democrats and liberals, said
Austrian journalist Karl Pfeifer, who attended the meeting.
   ``We do not strive to hold power, but we want to control
power,'' Kis was quoted as saying.
   Sandor Csoori, a leading member of the forum, said he received
official permission to publish a journal called Credit every other
week beginning in November.
   Delegates told a news conference that dissidents who have been
able to write only for underground publications would be given a
chance to contribute legally to the forum's journal.
</TEXT>
