<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAds 1stLd-Writethru a0745 09-04 1033</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negative Advertising Likely in Close Presidential Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf Rogich refused with 2 grafs to include
background on Massachusetts furlough program.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most negative political advertising
campaign ever is likely this fall from two presidential candidates
who are close in the polls, close on the issues and far from shy
about going on the offensive.
   Students of political advertising say media drives by the George
Bush and Michael Dukakis campaigns are likely to begin on an upbeat
note.
   But viewers shouldn't expect sunshine and roses on the air.
Critical ads ranging from mild comparisons to outright blasts are
planned by independent groups and the two parties, and the
candidates are expected to follow suit later in the season.
   Ultimately, the race will be ``the most negative in the history
of TV,'' predicted Kathleen Jamieson, a University of Texas
professor and author of two books on political communications.
   Democrat Dukakis and Republican Bush both scheduled traditional
Labor Day week media assaults, with at least one of them employing
a soft sell as the campaign season formally begins.
   ``Our plan is to be on the air with ads about Michael Dukakis'
record,'' said Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach. ``The major thrust of
the first wave will be cutting taxes, balancing budgets, putting
people to work, cutting crime and taking charge of our economic
future. Those are ads that George Bush can't make.''
   Dach would not say how much money will be spent on the first
wave but he said it will ``hit a lot of states... We intend these
ads to be seen by people, not just to be read about.''
   The Bush campaign is more closemouthed about its plans, although
it has been reported that a three-week, $1 million TV campaign will
start this week in California.
   ``We're firm about not discussing any media buying strategy or
any creative strategy,'' said Sig Rogich, Bush's director of
advertising operations. ``The Democrats will tell you (their
plans), and we appreciate it,'' he added.
   Rogich refused to comment on a report from campaign sources that
media adviser Roger Ailes has taped ads attacking Dukakis' defense
ideas and interviewing a Maryland couple victimized by convicted
murderer Willie Horton, a Massachusetts prisoner furloughed under
the state's program.
   Dukakis' predecessor, Republican Gov. Francis Sargent,
instituted the furlough program which Dukakis has supported.
Earlier this year, the Massachusetts governor reluctantly signed
legislation removing eligibility for first-degree murderers.
   At least one independent group plans a month-long, $540,000
assault on Dukakis via national cable networks starting Tuesday,
according to The Washington Post. The two 30-second ads produced
for Americans for Bush charge that Dukakis is soft on crime and
criminals. One cites the weekend prisoner furlough program and
Dukakis' opposition to the death penalty; the other focuses on
Horton.
   Dach says Dukakis plans to counter such attacks with ads touting
his effective crime-cutting record in Massachusetts. But he said
plans could change, depending on what comes out of the Republican
camp.
   Some relatively negative ads are coming from the Democratic and
Republican national committees, which are running multimillion
dollar generic media campaigns designed to promote party themes and
accomplishments as superior to the opposition.
   The GOP just completed a $4 million TV ad campaign that involved
three spots running for two weeks in every state. The ads claim
Americans have known only peace and prosperity under Republicans,
so why change?
   RNC spokesman Beth Brainard said plans for the timing and
content of next wave were up in the air but ``things are in place''
for another hit if it is needed. ``We're going to wait and see the
tenor of the campaign,'' she said. ``There may be a need to issue
specific ads of some kind that incorporate our message of peace,
prosperity, economic growth and seven years of success.''
   The DNC, financially equipped to run its first major generic
campaign this year, bought $75,000 worth of Texas airtime for a
quick counterpunch to the initial GOP ads and this week embarks on
a $1 million-plus generic ad campaign in seven to 12 swing states
likely to include California, Illinois, Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Missouri, New Jersey, Iowa, Wisconsin and Texas.
   The DNC ads, centered on the theme of ``bringing prosperity
home,'' are two-pronged. Some deal with competitiveness, world debt
and the deficit _ making America No. 1 again. Others talk about
economics on a more personal scale _ health care, child care, the
ability to buy homes and cars.
   The point, said Dach, is that ``if you're a family that's
working harder to stay in place, you can't afford to vote
Republican.''
   By the time the Bush-Dukakis campaign ends, Jamieson said,
negative TV advertising should surpass the high-water mark set
during the bitter 1964 Johnson-Goldwater battle, the most negative
to date.
   Observers cite a number of factors in explaining why they expect
a nasty TV campaign:
   _Attack ads were a major feature of both party's primary
contests this year, providing both precedent and raw material.
   _Bush and to some extent Dukakis are already giving very tough
speeches, and advertising traditionally is more negative than
speeches.
   _The candidates are neck-and-neck in the polls, giving them both
an incentive to go negative.
   _Neither candidate is particularly well-defined, making it
imperative that every attack be answered by a counter-attack lest
voters get and keep the wrong idea.
   _Both candidates are relatively centrist, with few significant
differences on issues. ``If you don't have broad issue
disagreements, then you concentrate on the personal,'' said Larry
Sabato, a University of Virginia professor specializing in election
media, polling and direct mail.
   Jamieson said the 1964 campaign was the most negative in the
number of negative ads produced and aired, but neither candidate
devoted more than one-third of his air time to negative ads.
   She and Sabato predicted negative messages will fill one-third
to one-half of each candidate's air time this year, and neither
will let negative ads eclipse positive ones.
   Why? ``It's just too risky in terms of backlash,'' Sabato said.
``Attacking is not presidential,'' added Jamieson. ``You can get by
with negative ads as long as the positive message is out there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880904-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LadyLiberty     09-04 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lady Liberty,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lady Liberty Has Long Been Sought As A Political Partner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While politicians normally don't want to be
linked with women other than their wives, there's one gal that
candidates have been fawning over for more than 100 years.
   She's 151 feet tall and stands demurely in New York Harbor.
   Candidates and their image makers say there's no better company
to be seen in _ especially on coast-to-coast television _ than that
of the Statue of Liberty.
   So coveted is she as political company that the campaigns of
Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, and
Republican vice presidential contender Sen. Dan Quayle clashed over
which of them would hold the lady's hand this Labor Day.
   Quayle prevailed, but only because he asked first, according to
the National Park Service. As the statue's custodian, the Park
Service takes great pains to assure the statue does not show
favorites.
   Still, she has been always been a willing companion since her
dedication by President Grover Cleveland in 1886. Woodrow Wilson,
Franklin D. Roosevelt and Richard Nixon have all paid calls on the
statue during re-election bids.
   ``The Statue of Liberty is something special,'' says Greg
Stevens of Ailes Communications, media consultant for George Bush.
   For tugging at voters' emotions, the grandiose statue and her
dramatic surroundings are a better backdrop than any Hollywood set.
   The statue took its prime place in the World War I war bond
drives of 1917, replacing the female Columbia as the
personification of America, says Park Service archivist Barry
Marino.
   No less an image maker than Alfred Hitchcock dropped a villian
from the statue's torch in ``Saboteur'' about 27 years before
putting Cary Grant and Grace Kelly on Mount Rushmore in ``North by
Northwest.''
   ``There's more emotion packed in the Statue of Liberty than
almost anything else in America,'' Stevens says.
   President Reagan chose Liberty State Park in Jersey City, N.J.,
to kickoff the 1980 campaign that put him in the White House. The
Hudson River-front park offers a dramatic view of the statue
against the skyscrapers of lower Manhattan.
   Wilson, running against New York Republican Charles Hughes in
1916, led an elaborate parade to relight the statue's torch after
it was damaged by sabatoge. Roosevelt, campaigning against Alf
Landon in 1936, gave a dramatic radio address by the statue during
its 50th anniversary celebration.
   This year, along with Quayle and Dukakis, former presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson has used the park as a political staging
ground.
   Both Dukakis and Quayle wanted to appear Monday at the
two-island Statue of Liberty-complex: Liberty Island, where the
statue stands, and Ellis Island, where millions of immigrants
entered the United States in the late 1800's and early 1900's.
   Since Quayle asked first, Dukakis had to settle for a tour of
Ellis Island on Saturday. He escorted his mother, Euterpe, a Greek
immigrant who arrived in this country via the island.
   ``It's first come, first served,'' explained Edie Shean-Hammond,
a Parks Service spokeswoman.
   She said rangers follow strict guidelines in issuing permits for
speeches and demonstrations. Access for daily visitors always comes
first, followed by equal access for anyone seeking to use the
statue as a soapbox.
   ``We have to play this really close to the book,'' Ms.
Shean-Hammond said.
</TEXT>
