<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlers Demand Government Permission To Shoot Stone-Throwers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with third Palestinian wounded, army
confirmation of incident, details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Bank Jewish settlers demonstrated Sunday
to demand government permission to shoot at Palestinian
stone-throwers. Soldiers in the occupied lands shot and wounded
three Palestinian protesters.
   At a Cabinet meeting, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir denied news
reports that he recommended expanding defense rules to allow
soldiers and civilians to fire back at stone-throwers in the
occupied lands, ministers said.
   Jewish settlers have been demanding both the army and settlers
be allowed to open fire on Palestinians throwing stones. Only
soldiers now are allowed to shoot at Arab firebombers. Settlers are
permitted to fire back only in the case of imminent danger to life.
   The controversy over those rules flared last week when a
U.S.-born Jewish settler accidentally shot and wounded two Israeli
soldiers. The settler, Gedalia Becker, stopped his car and fired in
the dark after a firebomb attack.
   About 200 residents of the West Bank settlement of Einav
occupied a park opposite Shamir's office Sunday and said they can't
live in their settlement because government policies don't allow
adequate protection against stone-throwers.
   Small children and their mothers sat under tents marked ``Day
Care Center'' and ``Kindergarten,'' surrounded by six police vans
and about two dozen policemen.
   Einav secretary Baruch Lior said two people from his settlement
of 40 families have been hit in the head in stone-throwing attacks
the last 10 days.
   ``We demand an elementary right to protect our lives. The army
is doing everything it can, but the government ties its hands. Can
the government say it did not spill this blood?'' Lior said.
   An elderly injured settler, Shlomo Levi, lay nearby on a
stretcher, a blood-stained bandage on his head. Levi was surrounded
by praying Jews, one of whom held a prayer book and an Uzi
submachine gun on his knees.
   At Shamir's office, the Cabinet debated rules of opening fire.
Energy Minister Moshe Shahal of the Labor Party told Israel radio
he accused Shamir of trying to turn the occupied lands into a
``wild West where each one takes the law in his hands.''
   Shahal's attack followed media reports that Shamir, head of the
rival Likud bloc, supports the idea of shooting stone-throwers.
   But Shamir denied supporting such a proposal, said his
spokesman, Avi Pazner.
   ``Israel is facing a wave of terror and has to meet it with a
firm hand. Security forces are working on methods to counter the
stone-throwing. ... It's good that the Cabinet debates it, and we
hope the army will soon find an answer,'' Pazner quoted Shamir as
telling the ministers.
   In the occupied West Bank, troops shot an 18-year-old
Palestinian, Suheil Harb, wounding him in the stomach, Arab reports
and hospital officials said. They said he was wounded during a
clash with soldiers at Kafr Sur village, close to Einav.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, another Arab, 22-year-old Mahmoud
Abdel Fatah of Deir el Balah village, was shot in the leg,
officials at the Ahli Arab hospital in Gaza said.
   An official at Al Ittihad Hospital told The Associated Press
that 26-year-old Ibrahim Yussef Sohahmi was shot and seriously
wounded in the neck during a clash with Israeli soldiers in the
West Bank village of Silat el Harithiya, near Jenin.
   The army said it knew of no clash between soldiers and
Palestinians in Deir el Balah, confirmed that a Palestinian was
shot and lightly wounded in the leg in Kafr Sur and was
investigating the reported shooting in Silat el Harithiya.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8 against Israeli rule
in the occupied lands, 5,600 Arabs have been wounded, according to
Israeli army figures. At least 258 Palestinians and four Israelis
have died.
</TEXT>
