<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Television     09-04 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Television,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Normally Closed Communist Party Meeting Televised Live</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gorky residents received dramatic proof of the
greater openness in their nation's public affairs when local
Communist Party officials allowed a party meeting to be televised
live for the first time.
   During the broadcast, residents of the Volga River city 250
miles east of Moscow could call in and make proposals to the party
officials, the government newspaper Izvestia said Sunday.
   ``We hope the discussion of burning problems in the presence of
the people and with the help of television will become a standard
of party work,'' Ivan V. Chapanov, a senior Gorky party executive,
was quoted as saying.
   The newspaper said the broadcast of the Gorky regional party
organization's meeting on Saturday was a first for the region, but
it was believed to be the first time any body in the 20
million-member party had allowed a full, live broadcast of its
proceedings. The broadcast also was reported by the Tass news
agency.
   Despite Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's promotion of
``glasnost,'' or more openness in public affairs, deliberations of
party organizations up to the ruling Politburo continue to be held
in secret. Often their meetings are only sketchily reported to the
public.
   At a nationwide party conference held in Moscow this summer,
some delegates demanded more information be made public about the
work and responsibilities of party organizations and officials.
   Speaking in a telephone interview with Izvestia, Chapanov said
Saturday's plenary party meeting in Gorky ``was preceded by a month
of strenuous work for preparing the live broadcasting, which is
unusual so far in party practices.''
   A newspaper in Gorkey announced in advance the plan to televise
the regional party plenum, Chapanov said.
   Phone numbers that gave people access to the meeting hall were
also made public, he said.
   According to Chapanov, ``people appreciated the initiative. Some
50 telephone calls and proposals were registered during the work of
the session.''
   Izvestia and Tass did not make clear whether the Gorky regional
committee intended to continue allowing live coverage of its
sessions, or whether the practice could spread elsewhere.
   In the past, top Communist Party officials, including Ideology
Secretary Alexander N. Yakovlev, have defended the party's practice
of holding meetings behind closed doors, saying the need for
greater openness in government does not oblige the party, legally a
private body, to open its proceedings to all.
</TEXT>
