<HEAD>Dissident Says Government Has `To Face Reality' To End Chaos</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Solarz comments, picks up
graf 4 pvs `No major...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Aung Gyi said Sunday
that Burma's rulers must ``face the reality'' and allow an interim
government to usher in immediate democracy and end nationwide chaos.
   Meanwhile, U.S. Congressman Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., said he
would introduce a measure next week in Congress expressing U.S.
support for a rapid transition to multi-party democracy in Burma.
   Speaking at a Bangkok news conference after a two-day trip to
Burma, Solarz said Burma's political future would probably be
decided in the next week.
   ``I think there is no question that Burma is on the dawn of a
new era of democracy,'' Solarz said. ``The only question is whether
the new era will emerge peacefully ... or whether it will be the
product of chaos, anarchy and violence.''
   At their meeting in Rangoon earlier Sunday, Aung Gyi told Solarz
the entire country rejected the government's plan for gradual
change.
   Solarz met separately with two other protest leaders: former
Defense Minister Tin Oo and Aung San Suu Kyi, daughter of late
Burmese independence leader Aung San. Solarz also lunched at the
Parliament Building with President Maung Maung.
   No major rallies were held in the capital Sunday, but protest
leaders called for daily demonstrations this week leading up to a
nationwide general strike Thursday.
   Solarz chairs the Asian and Pacific Affairs Subcommittee of the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. He has been a critic of repressive
governments in Asia and said he was visiting Rangoon to see what
the United States could do to encourage democracy.
   Solarz asked Aung Gyi his reaction to Maung Maung's plan for the
Burma Socialist Program Party to meet on Sept. 12 to consider a
popular vote on whether to end 26 years of one-party rule.
   ``The whole country is against it,'' said Aung Gyi, who was
recently released from a month of detention for criticizing the
party's harsh repression of dissent and ruinous economic policies.
   ``Government employees are on strike, the administration has
practically broken down, the situation has deteriorated very fast
and is now beyond control,'' Aung Gyi said.
   ``The whole country demanded immediate formation of an interim
government to ease the situation. The government has to face the
reality.''
   Aung Gyi said he believes Ne Win, who took power in a 1962
military coup in but officially resigned in July, still wields
``100 percent'' power.
   Hardliner Sein Lwin replaced Ne Win, but his 17-day rule was
ended by massive and bloody street protests that left 112 dead by
government count. Maung Maung took over Aug. 19 as the first
civilian leader since 1962.
   Aung Gyi said the people had tolerated their government for many
years, but recent months brought ``a series of intolerable things.''
   He said these included the government's voiding of a large
portion of currency notes without compensation in September and
rice shortages in a nation that once was the world's largest
exporter.
</TEXT>
