<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTLPurchase     09-04 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Purchase,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Is Readying to Take Over PTL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker offered assurances Sunday he'll
have the money this week to back up his $165 million offer for PTL.
   Bakker said in a telephone interview from his Fort Mill office
that he has been working 15-hour days in anticipation of regaining
the TV ministry he left in 1987 in a sex and money scandal.
   ``We have made quite a few contacts'' with bankers, Bakker said.
``When the contracts (to take over PTL) are ready, we'll have the
money to back it up.''
   He said he hopes he and his wife, Tammy, will be back on the air
on Sept. 12.
   On Friday, PTL bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton said he
was ``very, very skeptical'' about whether Bakker would come up
with the cash to back up his offer. If Bakker does not have a $3
million letter of credit by Tuesday, Benton said, he will start
considering other offers for the ministry's assets.
   A least four other offers ranging from $113 million to $200
million have been made for PTL, officials said.
   Benton has a deadline of Saturday to present a buyer to U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds for approval. The evangelical
empire filed for bankruptcy in June 1987, three months after the
scandal over Bakker's sexual liaison with Jessica Hahn.
   Bakker said working out deals with banks is especially difficult
during a holiday weekend, but a Midwestern bank, one in Atlanta and
another in Tennessee are interested in handling the funds from the
Greek investors he said are are backing his offer.
   Bakker declined to identify the investors or the banks.
   His lawyer, Jim Toms, said in a telephone interview from
Hendersonville, N.C., that some banks are leery of involvement
because of the controversy surrounding Bakker, but he feels certain
one will cooperate before the week ends.
   The evangelist said he's readying for the takeover by asking
experts for advice on such things as TV production, hotel
management, direct mailings, accounting and musical production.
   Bakker, who was defrocked by the Assemblies of God, said the
denomination has ``nothing to do with what we're doing.'' He said
he is an ordained minister of the Faith Christian Fellowship and
the new PTL will be under that church's guidance.
   He said that he knew some viewers have lost faith in him but
that his name recognition has increased dramatically since he left
the ministry and he expects to more than make up for the loss.
   ``Sure we have people who are turning their backs on us and will
turn their backs on us,'' he said. ``But we're known by so many
millions more. We're excited about it.''
</TEXT>
