<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heads Heads are are spinning spinning in
northern New Jersey after this weekend's 54th annual International
Twins Association convention.
   Cynthia Apacible at the hospitality desk at the Meadowlands
Hilton said the staff was slowly becoming accustomed to the sight
of 150 sets of twins _ 150 sets of twins _ roaming the lobby.
   ``The first day we all tried to figure out the differences
between them,'' said Ms. Apacible. ``I'm married to a fraternal
twin but I can't tell the difference on some of these people.''
   On Friday, the twins toured New York Harbor aboard the cruise
ship ``Spirit of New York.''
   ``The crew on the cruise ship was really freaking out,'' said
Cary Clark, 24, who is actually a triplet from Edmund, Okla. ``The
ones who are identical also dress alike. The bus drivers were all
pretty fascinated.''
   For Kathleen and Irene Grider, being identical twins and having
names that rhymed wasn't enough. The sisters from Durant, Okla.,
were singers in a country western band and married two band members
who were brothers.
   They still live next to each other and both have seven children.
