<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru a0714 09-04 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Against Ethnic Albanians Draw 100,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Sunday demonstration, two
others Saturday; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands marched in a Serbian city
Sunday to protest alleged harassment by ethnic Albanians in the
southern province of Kosovo, one of four weekend rallies that drew
more than 100,000, news reports said.
   Serbs and Montenegrins rallied in four cities during the weekend
to protest discrimination against non-Albanians in the province.
   More than 10,000 people, including a few hundred Serbs and
Montenegrins from Kosovo, held a rally Sunday in Crvenka in
Vojvodina province about 125 miles northwest of Belgrade, the state
news agency Tanjug reported.
   Demonstrators shouted ``give us weapons, we go to Kosovo'' and
``army to Kosovo'' at the weekend rallies, the reports said.
   Some shouted ``an end to genocide,'' referring to their
increasing accusations of persecution of Serbs and Montenegrins in
Kosovo, where Albanians make up 90 percent of the population.
   According to official statistics, more than 34,000 Slavs have
left Kosovo since bloody riots in 1981, when the government said
nine people were killed.
   Albanians in Kosovo contend, however, that economic problems are
the main factor forcing emigration.
   Some people at the rally in Crvenka sang a song in praise of
Serbian Communist Party chief Slobodan Milosevic. Milosevic wants
to increase his republic's control over the nominally autonomous
provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo, and many Serbs and Montenegrins
have welcomed the idea as a way of promoting their rights.
   At the largest demonstration of the weekend, nearly 70,000
rallied Saturday at Smederevo, about 30 miles south of Belgrade,
Tanjug said. About 20,000 Serbs have migrated to Smederevo from
Kosovo since World War II.
   A second rally Saturday brought together more than 20,000 people
at Kovin on the Danube opposite Smederevo, and about 2,000 others
demonstrated at Sombor, about 90 miles northwest of Belgrade, the
news agency said.
   The rallies defy pleas from national Communist Party leaders to
refrain from taking the Kosovo conflict to the streets.
</TEXT>
