<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-04 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over Much Of The East, Hot In West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell over much of the eastern third of the nation Sunday,
with heavy rain in the Gulf states, and the West Coast was
unseasonably hot.
   By Sunday afternoon, more than 5 inches of rain had fallen at
Meridian, Miss., since Saturday afternoon. During the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT, 3.01 inches of rain fell at Meridian, with 1.87
inches at Mobile, Ala.
   Locally heavy rain over two days saturated the ground of
southeastern Louisiana, and some rivers and bayous north of Lake
Pontchartrain were expected to rise to a few feet above flood stage
during the next few days.
   Rain fell throughout the East Coast states ahead of a cold front
in the Appalachians. Rain was widespread from New England to
Virginia and rain and scattered thunderstorms extended southward
toward the eastern Gulf Coast states.
   One to 3 inches of rain fell in northeastern Tennessee and
southwestern Virginia, with more than 4 inches in Wise County, Va.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed under an upper level
low pressure system over Ohio, Lower Michigan, northern Indiana and
Illinois.
   Heavy rain on Saturday caused the Rolling Fork River at Boston,
Ky., to rise more than 27 feet in 24 hours. It was expected to
crest just over flood stage Monday with only minor flooding.
   Strong high pressure over the West combined with an offshore
flow to produce scorching temperatures along coastal sections of
southern California.
   Los Angeles reached 105 degrees by noon PDT and San Diego warmed
to a record 104, temperatures between 20 and 25 degrees above the
normal highs for this time of the year. Fullerton had the highest
reading in the Los Angeles area at noon at 108.
   As far north as the northern end of the San Joaquin Valley,
Redding, Calif., hit 105 degrees by noon.
   Hurricane Uleki was more than 300 miles southwest of Honolulu
and began to move to the west.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to the 108 at Fullerton. Sunday
morning's low was 30 at Estes Park, Colo.
   For Monday, scattered showers were forecast from the Great Lakes
across the upper Ohio Valley to the northern and middle Atlantic
Coast states. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over eastern sections of the Carolinas across southern Georgia to
Florida and the central Gulf Coast region. Widely scattered
thunderstorms were forecast over the lower Rio Grande Valley of
southern Texas and the mountains of the Southwest.
   Highs in the upper 50s were predicted over northern Michigan; in
the 60s from the upper Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes to
sections of New York and Pennsylvania; in the 90s over sections of
Florida and Texas; in the 80s and 90s over much of the western
third of the nation; well over 100 across the desert Southwest, and
in much of California; and in the 70s and 80s across most remaining
areas between the Rockies and the East Coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
