<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Angola     09-04 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Angola,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader Says Cubans Adding Troops, Planning Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Angola's
anti-communist rebels claimed Cuba now has 60,000 troops in Angola
and is planning to attack his guerrilla forces within days.
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said Cuba has sent 10,000 more
soldiers to Angola in recent weeks and the Cuban-Angolan forces
have used a recent cease-fire to move farther south in Angola and
position themselves for an offensive.
   ``There are now 60,000 Cubans in Angola and they are prepared to
launch attacks within days,'' Savimbi said. ``The Cubans didn't
come here to wave goodbye. It is an initiative for an offensive.''
   Savimbi made his comments Saturday at his headquarters in Jamba,
a rebel stronghold in southern Angola. The Associated Press in
Johannesburg received a videotape of his remarks.
   Angola, Cuba and South Africa agreed on Aug. 8 to a cease-fire
in Angola's civil war as part of a regional peace initiative, but
Savimbi's National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
known as UNITA, did not participate in the negotiations.
   Portugal granted Angola independence in 1975 and the Marxist
Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola defeated UNITA
fighters in a battle for power.
   UNITA, with U.S. and South African backing, then began a
guerrilla campaign and Cuba sent troops to the southern African
country to help the government.
   Savimbi has said his guerrillas will continue the war because
they were not included in the cease-fire talks that were mediated
by U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker.
   Some U.S. officials in Washington last week told The Associated
Press that Cuba had increased its troop strength in Angola to
60,000, but the U.S. State Department said Friday it still
estimated the Cuban forces at 50,000.
   A new round of peace talks between South Africa, Cuba, Angola
and U.S. mediators is scheduled this week in Brazzaville, Congo.
   South Africa said Tuesday that it had withdrawn all of its
forces from Angola.
   It also said it is prepared to begin withdrawing its troops from
South-West Africa on Nov. 1 and to allow the territory to hold
independence elections next June 1 if the Cubans are out of Angola
by June. Sources involved in the last round of negotiations said
the Cubans offered to withdraw from Angola over a 24-month period.
   South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, is located between
Angola and South Africa and has been administered by South Africa's
white-controlled government since the end of World War I under a
mandate of the defunct League of Nations. The United Nations
repudiated that mandate but South Africa has rejected U.N.
resolutions calling for immediate independence for the territory.
   South Africa, with U.S. backing, has insisted that the Cuban
forces must first withdraw from Angola.
   Savimbi called the talks dealing with the withdrawal of Cuban
and South African troops from Angola ``a cosmetic solution to peace
when (the participants) know they are going to leave behind a war.''
   He said he supported U.S. efforts to end the 13-year-old
conflict but claimed Crocker was ``giving all the cards'' to the
Angolan government.
</TEXT>
