<HEAD>Dukakis' 2-1 Lead in Iowa Disappears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis' nearly 2-1
early summer lead over Republican George Bush in Iowa has
disappeared, according to a statewide poll released Sunday.
   The Des Moines Register's telephone survey of 687 likely voters
found 47 percent supporting Dukakis and 42 percent backing Bush, a
difference almost erased by the poll's 3.8 percentage point margin
of error. Eleven percent remain undecided.
   Last June, Dukakis led Bush 60 percent to 28 percent.
   Eighty-five percent of those surveyed who said they were
Republicans said they favor Bush, compared to 73 percent in a
similar poll last June.
   A much larger swing occurred among voters aged 18 to 24, who now
favor Bush by a 57-39 percent margin. In June, this group favored
Dukakis by a 70-25 percent margin.
   The poll was conducted Aug. 29-31.
</TEXT>
