<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialPoll     09-04 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Poll,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Voters Know Little of Bush, Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the presidential election nine weeks off,
sizable numbers of likely voters say they don't know much about the
candidates and feel the contenders are avoiding the issues, Time
magazine reported Sunday.
   A poll conducted for the magazine last week found improvement in
Republican George Bush's ratings for trustworthiness and
reliability and declines for Democrat Michael Dukakis in terms of
trustworthiness and experience.
   Overall, 47 percent of the 1,103 likely voters nationwide
favored Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, to
42 percent for Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas. The margin
of error was three points, meaning the race statistically was a
dead heat.
   That result was among voters who are registered and considered
likely to vote. Among all registered voters _ 1,474 of them in the
poll _ the race was even tighter: 44 percent for the Republicans,
42 percent for the Democrats.
   Time's survey, conducted Thursday and Friday, found that public
opinion remained largely unformed about the candidates as the
campaign enters its final stretch, and large swings in support
remained possible. A fifth of the likely voters backing each ticket
said they might change their minds.
   Fully 50 percent of the likely voters said they knew ``not much
at all'' about Dukakis and what kind of president he would be, and
29 percent said that about Bush, despite Bush's nearly eight-year
tenure as vice president.
   About half the likely voters said Bush was ``avoiding the real
issues,'' and nearly as many, 44 percent, said that of Dukakis.
   But Bush, who caught up in the polls with Dukakis after the
Republican convention last month, was rated favorably by 58 percent
of the likely voters, compared to a 49 percent favorable rating for
Dukakis. Each of the men was rated unfavorably by a third of the
likely voters.
   Moreover, 58 percent rated Bush as ``someone you can trust,'' up
from 48 percent in a Time poll in April, and 60 percent said Bush
could handle an international crisis, up from 51 percent in April.
   Fifty-three percent rated Dukakis as trustworthy, down from 61
percent in April, and 43 percent said he has the experience to be
president, down from 53 percent in April.
   Bush was rated far better on experience _ 83 percent _ and
Dukakis was viewed as reliable in a crisis by just 40 percent.
However, 72 percent said Dukakis cares about average Americans; 57
percent said so of Bush.
   Forty percent in the survey rated Dukakis as ``too liberal,''
indicating that Bush's attacks on ideological grounds have had some
effect.
   But while Bush has tied himself to President Reagan's record, 51
percent in the poll said they wanted the next president to ``follow
different policies,'' to 42 percent who favored continuing Reagan's
policies.
</TEXT>
