<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IntellectualCruise     09-04 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intellectual Cruise,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Ship, Oil Ship That Were Hemmed In By Ice Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Coast Guard icebreaker early Sunday
freed an oil company research-support vessel stranded in arctic
ice, hours after a ship carrying intellectuals on an educational
journey got free of the ice by itself, authorities said.
   The icebreaker Polar Star had been in the Arctic Ocean on a
mapping mission when it was diverted last week to help the cruise
ship Society Explorer, which was hemmed in by the ice.
   The cruise ship worked free of the ice, but meanwhile the Amoco
vessel, the Shaleen Nicholas, reported it was hemmed in about 30
miles southeast of Point Barrow.
   Coast Guard Lt. Greg Stewart in Juneau said the Polar Star
reached the Amoco vessel at about 7 a.m. Sunday and broke it free.
   The Society Explorer, which had 149 passengers and crew members
aboard, is operated by Society Expeditions Cruises of Seattle,
which specializes in journeys to unconventional destinations,
including Antarctica, and emphasizes libraries and lectures.
   The captain of the ship requested help Thursday when the ship
was near Point Barrow. A day later, the Shaleen Nicholas reported
it also was caught in the Beaufort ice.
   The Coast Guard said crews reported no danger related to the ice
problem. Officials had said the ice is unusually prevalent for this
time of year.
</TEXT>
