<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0794 09-04 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0794,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Rest Up For Labor Day Campaign Kickoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `The vice,' to UPDATE
with Time Magazine poll; INSERTS 5 grafs after 14th graf pvs,
`Bennett, who, with comment from Paul Simon and Brookline official;
EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and George Bush rested up Sunday for the
traditional Labor Day kickoff of the presidential campaign while
GOP vice presidential contender Dan Quayle stumped in the South,
telling stock car drivers what the candidates soon will hear _
``Gentlemen, start your engines.''
   Quayle ended his Southern swing with a rally in Richmond, Va.,
where he told the crowd, ``the South is going for George Bush.''
   ``I can't tell you what an upbeat feeling we have had on that
Southern swing,'' Quayle said. ``We're going all the way to the
White House because we are the party of the future.''
   Quayle, on his second solo campaign trip, visited Louisiana,
Arkansas, Mississippi, Alabama, Florida, South Carolina and
Virginia before traveling to Newark, N.J., for a Labor Day
appearance at Liberty Island.
   Democratic nominee Dukakis spent Sunday in Boston, preparing for
a Labor Day tour that includes stops in Philadelphia, Detroit, St.
Louis and Chicago.
   The vice president relaxed in Washington D.C. before embarking
on a West Coast trip to Oregon, Washington and the biggest
electoral prize _ California with its 47 votes.
   Bush received encouraging news from the latest Time Magazine
poll of 1,103 likely voters nationwide, which found that 47 percent
favor the Republican ticket while 42 percent prefer the Democrats.
The margin of error was three points, meaning the race
statistically was a dead heat.
   The survey, conducted Thursday and Friday, also found that
public opinion about the candidates remained largely unformed, and
major swings in the support remained possible.
   Bush, who caught up in the polls with Dukakis after the
Republican convention last month, was rated favorably by 58 percent
of the likely voters, compared to a 49 percent favorable rating for
Dukakis. Each of the men was rated unfavorably by a third of the
likely voters.
   Although the Republican nominee took a respite from campaigning,
two of his surrogates used television appearances to lash out at
Dukakis' record on education and labor.
   Education Secretary William Bennett, in an appearance on
NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' said Dukakis is a member of an elitist
Massachusetts crowd that has ``disdain for the simple and basic
patriotism of most Americans,'' including the reciting of the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   Bennett said the pledge is ``the ABCs of education,'' and added:
``If you have trouble with the pledge, you're going to have trouble
with a lot of things down the road.''
   In 1977, Dukakis vetoed legislation requiring mandatory
recitation of the pledge in public schools after Massachusetts'
highest court, citing U.S. Supreme Court precedent, said the
legislation was unconstitutional.
   Last month, Dukakis defended his decision, saying that although
he encourages children to say the pledge the issue centered on the
measure's constitutionality.
   Bennett said he lived in that ``Brookline-Cambridge world for
eight years,'' referring to Dukakis' hometown and the site of
Harvard University. ``These are people who don't like things like
the pledge. They have disdain for the simple and basic patriotism
of most Americans.''
   Asked if he was accusing Dukakis of disdain for patriotism,
Bennett said, ``I think the crowd with which he runs ... do think
they are smarter. You know, they have these advanced attitudes.
They don't like what most Americans think and believe.''
   Bennett's comments drew cries of foul from former Democratic
candidate Paul Simon, who described himself as Dukakis' point man
on education, and officials in Brookline.
   ``George Bush as education president would be easier to believe
if he had been an education vice president,'' Simon said in a
statement. ``There's no evidence George Bush ever raised his voice,
picked up a phone, or lifted a finger to protest the miserable
education record of this administration.''
   Jeffrey Allen, chairman of the Brookline Board of Selectmen,
demanded an apology from Bennett.
   ``My reaction is one of outrage that the secretary of education
on national television sees fit to question the patriotism and
committment to this nation of a town of 59,000 people,'' Allen said
Sunday afternoon.
   ``I believe he owes this town an apology,'' he said.
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin, who appeared on ABC-TV's ``This
Week With David Brinkley,'' said she did not see plans that Dukakis
has had in Massachusetts ``that are transferrable to the nation at
large.''
   Bush's running mate took a break from touting the Republican
ticket and criticizing the Democrats. Indiana Sen. Quayle attended
the Southern 500 stock car race in Darlington, S.C., where he was
given the honor of telling the drivers: ``Gentlemen, start your
engines.''
   At the opening ceremonies of the race, he received a smattering
of boos from the audience when he was introduced.
   Later Sunday, Quayle attended a private fund-raiser in Richmond
and flew on to Newark where he prepared for the speech he will give
Monday morning in the shadow of the Statue of Liberty.
   Labor Day marks the official countdown to the November election
but political events, including the furor over the selection of
Quayle, forced the candidates to start in earnest earlier this year.
   The contest remains close as reflected in three state polls
released Sunday.
   In Iowa, Dukakis' nearly 2-1 early summer lead has disappeared
and he now leads Bush, 47-42 percent. The Des Moines Register poll
of 687 likely voters, conducted Aug. 23-31, had a margin of error
of 3.8 percentage points.
   In the same poll taken in June, Dukakis led Bush by a 60-28
percent margin.
   In a survey conducted for the Wilmington News-Journal papers in
Delaware, Bush led Dukakis 38 percent to 34 percent with 28 percent
of the 1,824 registered voters undecided. The poll, conducted Aug.
19-26, had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
   Bush also led Dukakis in a poll of 502 registered voters in
Alabama. The survey for the Birmingham News found Bush favored by
50.7 percent and Dukakis by 34 percent. The survey, with a margin
of error of 5 percentage points, was conducted Aug. 27-31.
</TEXT>
