<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokelessCigarette     09-04 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smokeless Cigarette,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smokeless Cigarette Gets Varied Marks in Informal Taste Test</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ A smokeless cigarette that R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co. plans to test market apparently is not for
everyone.
   ``It smells like a tennis shoe burning,'' said Tom Martin of
Danville, Va., who took a puff during an informal taste test last
week. ``A Reebok.''
   ``Woody,'' added Shawn Evans of Columbus, Ohio.
   The unscientific survey was conducted by the Winston-Salem
Journal.
   Reynolds Tobacco announced last week it would begin
test-marketing the cigarette, called Premier, Oct. 1 in St. Louis,
and in the Arizona cities of Phoenix and Tucson.
   Reynolds, one of the nation's largest cigarette manufacturers
and a subsidiary of Atlanta-based RJR Nabisco Inc., began selling
the new brand last week to distributors, supermarkets and discount
chains in the three cities.
   Company spokesmen say the product simulates smoking by heating a
capsule containing tobacco flavor pellets instead of tobacco. When
a smoker lights the cigarette, heat filters through the pellets and
the little bit of tobacco packed around the unit.
   It produces no odor and only a trace of ash or smoke that could
irritate people nearby, the company says. It also reportedly
contains fewer of what Reynolds calls ``controversial compounds,''
the hazardous byproducts associated with cigarette smoke.
</TEXT>
