<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Deportees     09-04 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Deportees,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Appeal Deportation Orders At Public Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians fighting
deportation orders pleaded their case Sunday in an open hearing _
the first time the army permitted the public to attend an appeals
session.
   Defense lawyers lauded the army's decision but said due process
was still being violated because prosecutors could submit ``secret
evidence'' without having to show it to the defense.
   Said Barakat, 32, a Moslem fundamentalist leader, and Riad
Adjour, 26, accused of being a PLO activist, are among 25
Palestinians from the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
fighting deportation orders issued last month.
   Since the Dec. 8 start of the Palestinian uprising in the
occupied territories, Israel has expelled 33 Arabs. The practice
has been denounced by the United States and other Western nations
as violating international human rights conventions.
   ``There is no hope, no justice for me here, but I don't want to
go without fighting,'' Barakat told the tribunal.
   The hearing before a three-member military review committee took
place at the army's Gaza City headquarters and was attended by
three journalists and about two dozen relatives of the defendants.
   Barakat and Adjour sat quietly on a wooden bench as the
prosecutor, Capt. Meir Klinger, read the charges against them.
   Klinger said Barakat, a high school teacher from the Gaza Strip
town of Bani Suheila, was a chief ideologust of Islamic Jihad, a
Moslem fundamentalist organization pledged to the destruction of
Israel.
   He also said that Barakat, who was arrested May 11, signed a
15-page statement in which he acknowledged writing underground
leaflets inciting anti-Israeli violence.
   ``We had enough evidence to put him on trial,'' Klinger told the
panel. ``Instead, we decided to deport him because experience has
shown that fanatic Islamic leaders usually continue their hostile
activities in jail.''
   The prosecutor said Adjour was a Palistine Liberation
Organization activist who led outlawed ``popular committees'' of
Palistinian miliants in the Daraj neighborhood of Gaza City.
Klinger claimed Adjour distributed PLO funds and ordered the
burnings of stores whose owners ignored strike orders.
   In both cases Klinger submitted ``secret evidence,'' which
usually involves reports by Israel's Shin Bet security service. The
defense is barred from seeing such evidence on security grounds.
   ``You can't argue against secret evidence,'' said Fayez Abu
Rahme, one of the defense lawyers and head of the Gaza Lawyers
Association.
   After defense lawyers present their case in a separate session
the review panel will issue its recommendations. If it upholds the
deportation orders the defendants can appeal to the Supreme Court.
   Neither the review committee nor the Supreme Court has struck
down a deportation order since the uprising began.
   An Israeli lawyer, speaking on condition of anonymity, suggested
the hearings were opened to the public to provide more legitimacy
to the proceedings and defuse international criticism.
   But the defense lawyers expressed concern that Israel was
setting the stage for mass deportations.
   ``They used to deport just the leaders, now they're deporting
the small fish,'' said Tamar Pelleg, a lawyer representing Adjour
on behalf of the Association for Civil Rights in Israel. She noted
that Adjour had not been arrested previously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
