<HEAD>Bennett Attacks Dukakis On Patriotism, Pledge Veto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``Asked if ...'' to
UPDATE with response from Brookline official, Paul Simon; Picks up
8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Bennett defended ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William Bennett on Sunday
accused Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis of
running with a crowd that has ``disdain for the simple and basic
patriotism of most Americans.''
   Bennett, who leaves the Reagan administration later this month,
vowed to dog Dukakis on educational issues and accused the
Massachusetts governor of offering only ``empty, general, bland
platitudes'' on education.
   Speaking on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' Bennett said Dukakis's
record on education consists of his ``veto of the Pledge of
Allegiance.'' In 1977, the Massachusetts governor vetoed a measure
requiring mandatory recitation of the pledge in public schools
after the state's highest court, citing U.S. Supreme Court
precedent, said the legislation was unconstitutional.
   ``I encourage children to say the Pledge of Allegiance,''
Dukakis said during a campaign stop last month. ``I say the Pledge
of Allegiance. That's not the issue. The Republicans know it. ...
That law was unconstitutional.''
   Bennett called the pledge ``the ABCs of education,'' adding,
``If you have trouble with the pledge, you're going to have trouble
with a lot of things down the road.''
   ``I lived in that Brookline-Cambridge world for eight years,''
he said, referring to the town where Dukakis lives and the site of
Harvard University. ``These are people who don't like things like
the pledge. They have disdain for the simple and basic patriotism
of most Americans,'' said Bennett.
   Asked if he was accusing Dukakis of having disdain for
patriotism, Bennett said, ``I think the crowd with which he runs
... do think they are smarter. You know, they have these advanced
attitudes. They don't like what most Americans think and believe.''
   Jeffrey Allen, chairman of the Brookline Board of Selectmen,
later expressed ``outrage that the secretary of education on
national television sees fit to question the patriotism and
commitment to this nation of a town of 59,000 people.''
   ``I believe he owes this town an apology,'' Allen said.
   Democratic Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois, Dukakis' point man on
education issues, responded to Bennett's comments with a critique
of George Bush's track record on education.
   ``There's no evidence George Bush ever raised his voice, picked
up a phone, or lifted a finger to protest the miserable education
record of this administration,'' Simon said.
   Bennett defended his political statements as consistent with
positions he has taken as education secretary and said the Bush
campaign paid for his recent trip to California where he attacked
Dukakis on education.
   ``I think what George Bush is talking about is going to keep the
educational reform movement moving. What Mike Dukakis is talking
about is empty, general, bland platitudes,'' Bennett said.
</TEXT>
