<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarCleanup     09-04 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Car Cleanup,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Residents Turn Over, Push Cars Into Intersections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents frustrated by the city's failure
to clean up their neighborhood flipped some abandoned cars over and
pushed others into intersections, and one of the 23 vehicles caught
fire, police said.
   Angry residents of the impoverished north side neighborhood took
to the streets in a frenzy of protest Saturday when city trash
trucks drove by without picking up garbage from a cleanup effort,
police said.
   Capt. Gerald Baker said police were looking for the group of 15
or so men involved in the spree, but no arrests had been made by
Sunday morning. No injuries were reported.
   The protest was apparently triggered by the botched cleanup
effort and frustration over the hundreds of abandoned cars that
litter the area's streets and never get towed.
   ``There's cars here for six months,'' said neighbor Stella
Martin. ``You call and you call and nothing gets done. They were
told the only way the city would pick up the abandoned cars was if
they're in the middle of the streets.''
