<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     09-04 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Says People Oppose Return of Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Sunday
that many Filipinos oppose the return of ousted ruler Ferdinand
Marcos and have vowed to hold demonstrations if he comes back.
   In her weekly radio program, Mrs. Aquino said her government
would comply if the courts ruled that Marcos could return from
exile in Hawaii. But she said there has been no such ruling because
no criminal charges have been filed against him.
   A military-civilian uprising in February 1986 ousted Marcos and
carried Mrs. Aquino to power. Two weeks ago, Marcos filed a
petition with a Manila court asking that he be allowed to return
and confront a former Cabinet member scheduled to testify in
November on alleged corruption during the his 20-year rule.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos to return, citing
national security.
   ``Many people have sent letters and called up on the phone to
tell me that they don't want Ferdinand Marcos to come back yet,''
she said Sunday. ``Some people have sent word to me that they would
go out into the streets to protest the return of Marcos.''
   The government has been seeking to recover up to $10 billion
that it claims Marcos and his associates plundered from the country
but it has not filed criminal charges against Marcos. Under
Philippine law, a defendant's presence is required in criminal
proceedings.
   ``Since no criminal charges have been filed against the former
president, there is really no necessity yet for the courts to
probably call for him,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   Marcos had filed the petition seeking to return after the
anti-corruption court granted the solicitor-general's request for a
special hearing to ``perpetuate'' the testimony of former Public
Works Secretary Baltazar Aquino.
   Baltazar Aquino, who is not related to the president, had served
in Marcos' Cabinet. Government lawyers have said he will testify
about millions of dollars Marcos allegedly received in kickbacks
from Japanese firms. The lawyers said Baltazar Aquino's testimony
must be taken soon because he is ill.
   The court did say Marcos has the right to defend himself in the
proceedings that will begin Nov. 7 because the solicitor-general
declared he intended to use testimony in the hearing in a future
criminal suit against Marcos.
   The government has asked the court to reject Marcos' petition.
On Thursday the court gave Marcos 10 days to submit a written reply
to the government's motion.
</TEXT>
