<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Abort,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeoff Stalled by Slow Acceleration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trans World Airlines passenger jet aborted
takeoff Sunday from Los Angeles International Airport after the
pilot reported slow acceleration, authorities said.
   Flight 846 to Boston never left the runway, and no injuries were
reported from the 9:01 a.m. incident, said Dick Hallen, a duty
officer for the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The Lockheed L-1011, carrying an unknown number of passengers
and crew, was rolling toward takeoff when the pilot ``indicated to
the tower that they were slow to accelerate'' and decided not to
depart, Hallen said.
   ``He requested emergency equipment just in the event that they
may have had hot brakes (from slowing down),'' the officer said.
   The equipment was not needed and the plane returned to its gate,
Hallen said.
   The cause of the incident was under investigation, he added.
   TWA officials could not be reached immediately for comment.
   The L-1011 is a three-engine aircraft that can carry from 250 to
400 passengers.
