<HEAD>U.N. Mediator Says No Plans For Recess In Iran-Iraq Talks.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. mediator in the Iran-Iraq peace talks
said Sunday there are no plans to recess the talks despite bitter
disputes between the Persian Gulf neighbors.
   But Jan Eliasson, speaking at a news conference, said he was
having ``informal contacts'' with both delegations but declined to
give details about the talks, now in their 11th day.
   Foreign ministers Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz of
Iraq have not met face-to-face since the second day of the
negotiations. Instead, delegates from both sides, with or without
the ministers, have held separate meetings with U.N.
representatives.
   ``There's no recess planned for the time being,'' Eliasson said.
``We are in this intensive working phase and I am hopeful and
expect progress on the issues we discuss.''
   The Geneva talks are to arrange follow-up procedures for the
cease-fire that took effect Aug. 20 after nearly eight years of
fighting. The talks have bogged down over disagreements about troop
withdrawals and the Shatt-al-Arab waterway between Iran and Iraq
that leads into the northern gulf.
   Eliasson, who was appointed mediator on Thursday, was asked if
there had been any progress in the negotiations.
   He said ``to me it is progress that both sides sit in a meeting,
discuss problems of substance, and characterize the talks as
businesslike and constructive.''
   Aziz, after meeting with Eliasson Saturday, said the talks were
``still in square one'' and he again blamed Iran for the stalemate.
   Both sides have accused each other of violating the cease-fire
and Eliasson said the complaints had been submitted to U.N.
officials in Iran and Iraq ``but we haven't received any feedback
from them yet.''
