<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Delta-EmergencyCrews     09-04 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta-Emergency Crews,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Response Crews Learned From 1985 Crash, Official Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Delta-Investigation, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Changes in emergency procedures that
were implemented after the Delta Flight 191 tragedy three years ago
helped make a smooth response to last week's crash, an official
said Sunday.
   ``This emergency response appears to be one of the most
effective that I've ever seen,'' said Lawrence D. Roman, a
representative of the American Association of Airport Executives
and a member of the ``survival factors'' group of the National
Transportation Safety Board team investigating Wednesday's crash.
   Delta Flight 1141 crashed and burned on takeoff at Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport, killing 13. Ninety-five people,
including the three members of the cockpit crew, survived as the
Boeing 727 skidded to rest at the end of a runway.
   ``It would appear that on first impression that this response
was excellent,'' Roman said. ``I don't know of any screw-ups at all
in the whole operation.''
   He stressed that he was not speaking on behalf of the
investigation, but as a representative of the airport executives
association.
   Roman said changes made in emergency response procedures at the
airport since the Aug. 2, 1985, crash of Delta Flight 191,
including installation of cellular telephones in ambulances, helped
in evacuating survivors.
   Also, he said, an automated telephone system implemented at the
airport's Department of Public Safety office reduced the time it
took to notify rescue workers after the crash.
   Those procedures resulted from NTSB recommendations made after
the 1985 crash, which resulted in 137 deaths, Roman said.
   Meanwhile, eight crash survivors were released from hospitals
Saturday. Some recalled the crash and rescue operation, which they
said involved little panic.
   Stella Grigg, at age 80 the oldest person on the downed plane,
said she was pushed out of the aircraft through a hole near the
cockpit and caught by a group of men on the ground.
   ``I was thrust forward and back, even though I had a seat belt
on,'' she said. ``The plane tipped to the left and tipped to the
right and just skidded along.''
</TEXT>
