<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Yellowstone-Tourists     09-04 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone-Tourists,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Tourists Brave Smoke to Visit Yellowstone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke was billowing and about 150
people were evacuated both in and around Yellowstone National Park
on Sunday, but more than 200 square dancers decided the show must
go on.
   A 57,000-acre fire closing in on the park's northeastern
entrance apparently did not faze about 250 square dancers, who
gathered on the west edge of the park for the 33rd annual Knothead
Jamboree.
   ``Square dancers are tough. We can take what they dish out,''
said Betty Rae Bronson of Shelley, Idaho, who is that state's
chairwoman for this year's event. ``Or else we're Knotheads. That's
what we're called.''
   The dancers come from Montana, Wyoming, Idaho and Utah and have
held their jamboree each Labor Day weekend at West Yellowstone
since 1980.
   This year's attendance ``is about half what we had last year
because of the fire,'' Ms. Bronson said.
   Nancy Johnson of Missoula, the Montana co-chairman, said
attendance at the jamboree usually numbers closer to 800.
   ``It would've been too late to move it ... or cancel unless it
would have been an emergency situation or evacuation of the town,''
she said.
   So they pressed ahead with the festival, which began Saturday
and is to conclude Monday. But the event was hurt financially by
the low attendance and may not break even this year, Johnson said.
   The never-say-die square dancers had reserved a hall in the Fly
Fishing Center, which meant that fire officials, who had set up a
fire information center there, were obliged to move their operation
into two nearby tents until the jamboree ends.
   Meanwhile, tourists continued flocking to the nation's oldest
park, despite weeks of headline-making fires.
   ``We've never been here before. We just decided we wanted to see
Yellowstone,'' said Eugene Kistner of Carmi, Ill. His wife, Esther,
said they knew what to expect because they had been following the
fires' progress on television, but decided not to let that
interfere with their plans.
   ``We wanted to try it anyway,'' she said.
   ``We got to see everything we intended to see,'' Eugene Kistner
said.
</TEXT>
