<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Election 1stLd-Writethru   09-04 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Election, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0750,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita's Party, In Tax Reform Test, Wins Provincial Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Final results and details grafs 1-5. Pick 4th graf: The
victories were... but edits 8th graf pvs bgng: The three-way
race... to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's government passed
a key test in its bid to overhaul Japan's tax system when the
governing Liberal Democratic Party scored twin victories Sunday in
a provincial election.
   Final results Monday in conservative Fukushima province gave the
Liberal Democrats the governorship and a seat in Parliament's upper
House of Councilors.
   Officials said 81.2 percent of the eligible voters cast ballots
_ a record for Fukushima.
   Eisaku Sato won the gubernatorial race with 685,791 votes
compared to 461,350 for Toshio Hirose, a Liberal Party rebel who
opposed the tax changes, and communist candidate Masaru Kusano who
polled 61,630 votes in the northern province.
   Liberal Democrat Kentaro Ishihara won the House of Councilors
seat with 702,940 votes to 312,203 for Kazuo Ishiga of the
Socialist Party and 186,503 for Yumiko Abe of the Communist Party.
   The victories were a boost to the governing party's attempt to
reform tax laws to include a controversial 3 percent consumption
tax on nearly all goods and services.
   Takeshita has staked his political life on the success of the
tax measure. He said this year, ``I am prepared to take political
responsibility if the tax reform cannot be realized.''
   It is Japan's third attempt to overhaul a tax system drafted by
American occupation officials shortly after World War II. Previous
failures dealt embarrassing political setbacks to two of
Takeshita's predecessors.
   Opposition parties had hoped to spark nationwide resistance to
the consumption tax, making the governor's election a showdown on
the reform proposals.
   Takeshita's party had not officially endorsed either Sato or
Hirose in the gubernatorial campaign.
   ``The results have stirred high interest ... they will exert
great influence on the tax reform,'' said a statement from
Takeshita on Ishihara's victory.
   ``As the governing party we have taken the long view and
advocated the necessity of tax reform. We gained the voters'
understanding with our efforts,'' Takeshita said.
   The Japan Socialist Party blamed the governing party for its
defeat. ``The conservative Liberal Democratic Party's disunity
alone was emphasized by its skillful concealment and ambiguous
treatment of the consumption tax,'' Secretary General Tsuruo
Yamaguchi said in a statement.
   The conservative victories stymied opposition hopes of building
up momentum against the tax reform. Last year, a gubernatorial
victory by the Socialists in another conservative stronghold
prompted nationwide protests that led to the defeat of then-Premier
Yasuhiro Nakasone's tax reform proposals.
   Faced with a political opposition united against the tax plan,
however, Takeshita's government has managed to win agreement only
on initial cuts in income taxes. Parliamentary deliberation on the
rest of the package has been stalled by a stock-profit scandal
involving several politicians and aides.
   The package calls for reducing Japan's heavy reliance on direct
taxes by trimming income and corporate taxes and introducing the
consumption tax. Critics say the plan falls short of the
government's goal of easing inequities in the present system and
preventing future increases in the consumption tax rate.
   Although the Liberal Democrats hold commanding majorities in
both houses of Japan's parliament, tradition and popular resistance
have kept the party from ramming through the proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880904-0083 </DOCNO>
