<HEAD>Romania Accuses Hungarian News Media of Distortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania on Sunday accused the Hungarian
news media of distorted coverage of events in Romania even after
the leaders of the two communist countries agreed to try to improve
relations.
   A major issue that has strained relations is Romania's plan to
raze some 7,000 villages, including hundreds of communities
populated mainly by ethnic Hungarians, and resettle the people in
agro-industrial centers as part of a land reform program. There are
about 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in Romania, which has a
population of 23 million.
   An editorial in Scinteia, the newspaper of the Romanian
Communist Party, said the Hungarian media is ``becoming the echo of
hostile, chauvinistic and nationalistic circles and groups.''
   Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu met with Hungarian Premier
Karoly Grosz in the Romanian town of Arad a week ago in the first
top-level meeting between the two countries in eleven years.
   Scinteia said Ceausescu told Grosz the Hungarian media ``distort
in their coverage the situation in Romania, give accounts that are
not real, including the program of modernization and organization
of settlements of the country, of improvement of the Romanian
people's living standard.''
   It reported Ceausescu also said those programs ``are internal
matters, the resolution of which is the exclusive concern of our
party, of the Romanian people.''
   The editorial said: ``The Romanian people are outraged by such
gross attempts (by the Hungarian media) to falsify the Romanian
realities and denigrate the Romanian policy, and most firmly
disapproves of such practices.''
   Some Hungarian officials have called Romania's resettlement
plan, which is to be completed by the year 2000, idiotic and ``a
crime against mankind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
