<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 2240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WesternHeat     09-04 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Heat,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Temperatures Set Along West Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 110-degree reading tied the city's all-time
record Sunday and the heat drove hundreds of thousands to beaches
for the Labor Day weekend, causing power outages and helping feed a
swarm of brushfires.
   To the north, Grants Pass, Ore., broke a 33-year-old record of
103 degrees with a 107-degree reading, and Spokane, Wash., baked
under a third day of record-breaking temperatures _ this time with
a little smoke added.
   The last time the temperature reached 110 in Los Angeles was
Sept. 1, 1955. The temperature easily beat the record high for the
date of 100 set in 1984.
   To the south, a record for the date of 107 was set at San
Diego's Lindbergh Field, surpassing a 1961 record of 95.
   Other triple-digit temperatures in southern California were Long
Beach, 104; Burbank, 106; Fullerton, 108; and Ontario, 110.
   Riverside and San Bernardino, usually the inland hot spots, were
cooler with 104 and 106 degrees, respectively.
   The hottest spot in California Sunday was about 300 miles
northeast of San Francisco at Red Bluff, which posted a record 118
degrees.
   Beach highways were jammed, with no parking available anywhere,
observers said. Guards at beaches near Los Angeles estimated some
775,000 people took to the sand, while lifeguards at Newport and
Huntington beaches in Orange County reported 207,000 people.
   It was so crowded ``you could probably hop from blanket to
blanket to avoid the hot sand ... play beach blanket bingo on your
way to the water,'' said Huntington State Beach lifeguard Jim Balok.
   Southern California Edison reported 1,000 customers without
electricity due to peak demand from air conditioners that knocked
out 425 transformers.
   Power outages also were reported in Watts and in Hancock Park,
home of Mayor Tom Bradley, but they were not believed caused by
demand related to the heat, said Dorothy Jensen, spokeswoman for
the city's Department of Water and Power.
   As the heat raged, so did the brush fires. Fast moving blazes
were reported in San Diego, Riverside, Orange, San Bernardino and
Ventura counties, with more than 2,800 acres charred.
   Sunday was the second day of the southern California heat wave.
The National Weather Service predicted lower temperatures for the
coast Monday, but continued high temperatures in inland areas for
Labor Day, with some relief reaching inland Tuesday.
   Other highs in Oregon Sunday included 103 at Medford, 102 at The
Dalles and 101 at Hermiston, none of which were records.
   In Washington, Spokane hit 96, four degrees higher than the
previous record for the date set in 1963, the weather service said.
It was the third day in a row that a daily record high was broken,
with Saturday's maximum of 98 equalling the all-time high
temperature for September.
   Spokane residents also had to put up with smoky skies from the
forest fires burning in the northeast part of the state.
</TEXT>
