<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SeattleBlackout 1stLd-Writethru a0759 09-04 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seattle Blackout, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0759,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electricity Finally Restored To Parts Of Downtown Seattle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 5-8 ``About half ... he said.'' to UPDATE with
status of power restoration Sunday night.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electricity flowed downtown again Sunday after a
three-day blackout that halted elevators in high-rises, thawed
frozen food and shut down air conditioners during one of the
hottest weeks in Seattle history.
   Power was finally restored to much of the 50-block area Saturday
night, but Seattle City Light asked customers to conserve power and
not turn on air conditioners until two more fire-damaged cables
could be repaired.
   Three days without electricity had taken their toll.
   ``Too many problem, too many problems,'' said Dae W. Kim as he
slowly began turning on the dozen coolers in his grocery and deli.
``I've got a headache.''
   About half the blacked-out area's customers began receiving
power via four repaired feeder cables at 6:47 p.m. Saturday. By
Sunday night, 90 percent of the affected customers had power back,
but there were load restrictions on four buildings, said Jim
Aguirre, a spokesman for the city-owned utility.
   Crews still were working on restoring a fifth feeder cable, and
the sixth feeder was expected to be brought back into service
Monday or later, Aguirre said.
   Until then, many buildings will have only partial power, since
they receive electricity from a combination of the cables, said
Hugh McIntosh, another City Light spokesman.
   At the twin towers of the 875-room Westin Hotel, for example,
full service was restored to the south tower early Sunday, while
the north tower remained on a generator, rented for $6,200 a week,
marketing director Dell Schooly said.
   The six cables were destroyed Wednesday by an unexplained
underground fire.
   City Light Superintendent Randall Hardy said the fire apparently
started in the City Light cables, in which power should have been
cut off by automatic current limiters that act when a cable gets
hot.
   Electricity also continued to flow through a nearby Metro
transit cable, powering electric trolleys, and that may have made
the fire worse, he said.
   When the power restoration began, patrols roamed the area to
make sure no fires were triggered by equipment left switched on
when the outage began.
   ``It went very smoothly. I have no reports of problems other
than the sprinkler in the Battery Street tunnel,'' which apparently
began wetting down the tunnel when it was tripped by the power
surge, McIntosh said.
   ``We called the fire department and told them it was their
problem.''
   Air conditioning was lost as temperatures soared to a September
record of 98 degrees Friday and to a record for the date of 92 on
Saturday. Sunday dawned with a cool fog and a forecast high of only
80 to 85.
   City Light had no estimate of its costs to restore power or of
damage from the fire.
   ``Our field people were really extending themselves, a lot of
them volunteering to go 16 hours, double shifts, until they could
get the thing done,'' McIntosh said.
   No injuries were reported and stepped-up police patrols were
credited with preventing break-ins.
   At the height of the blackout, city officials estimated that 90
percent of all businesses in the area were closed. The area has
about 130 restaurants, 55 shops in the popular Pike Place Market,
the large Bon Marche department store and several hotels, grocery
stores and taverns.
   Pike Place Market businesses saw a drop in traffic, even though
many shops never lost electricity.
   ``People think the whole market is closed,'' said Garth Wilson
of Jack's Fish Spot.
   The Red Cross served three meals a day to 150 to 250 elderly
residents stuck in the darkened area. Volunteers had to take some
meals up 13 flights in buildings where elevators were out of
operation.
</TEXT>
