<FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-TickerTalk     09-04 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ticker Talk,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts' Interest Rate Worries Get Specific</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As any casual follower of the stock market
knows, a lot of the market's recent woes have been blamed on rising
interest rates.
   But it is the way rates have been rising, even more than the
simple fact that they have been moving up, that particularly
troubles some analysts.
   With several nudges from the Federal Reserve, short-term
interest rates (on debt securities with lives of a year or less)
have climbed more sharply of late than long-term rates (on bonds
with maturities of up to 30 years).
   That means that what Wall Streeters call the yield curve, a
graphic representation of the relationship between short- and
long-term rates, is flattening.
   If it inverts _ that is, if short-term rates go higher than
long-term rates _ many analysts believe it would be a sign of
significant trouble for both the stock market and the economy.
   Normally, interest rates on long-term debt tend to be higher
than on short-term loans because long-term borrowers expose
themselves to greater risk that the purchasing power of their money
will be eroded by inflation, or that the issuer of the debt will
default.
   So when the yield curve tilts in the opposite direction, it is
widely taken as a sign that something is out of whack.
   Inverted yield curves showed up early in the bear markets and
recessions that occurred in 1973-74 and again at the beginning of
the 1980s.
   ``If the yield curve inverts, there is a very high probability
that a recession will follow,'' said Susan Berge Kent, an analyst
at Tucker, Anthony & R.L. Day Inc., in a recent commentary.
   Recently, she noted, the ratio of rates on three-month Treasury
bills to those on 30-year Treasury bonds stood at .78.
   ``If the ratio rises above .80 and the Fed does not cut the
discount rate, historical probability indicates that the yield
curve will invert,'' she said.
   Another cause for concern, in the view of Anthony Sorrentino,
technical analyst at Standard & Poor's Corp., is the fact that
rates on three-month T-bills, at more than 7 percent, are higher
than the Fed's discount rate, which it recently raised from 6
percent to 6.5 percent.
   ``Such a positive spread is a sign of a restrictive Federal
Reserve policy, which usually places downward pressure on the stock
market,'' Sorrentino said.
   ``Until the T-bill rate falls below the discount rate, this
measure will remain in a bearish mode.''
   Analysts at the financial advisory service Donoghue's
Moneyletter say managers of money market mutual funds have also
been sounding a warning about interest rates and the financial
outlook in recent months.
   As a group, these managers have been shortening the average
maturities of the securities in their portfolios.
   The standard motive for shortening maturities is to avoid or
minimize price declines for existing securities when interest rates
rise, and to have money available soon to invest at higher rates.
   ``When these managers believe interest rates are poised for a
rise, they invest their funds in shorter-term securities,'' the
newsletter said.
   ``Since the shortening began, the stock market generally has
been moving sideways, and it recently has declined in the face of
higher interest rates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
