<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Furr's-Wyatt     09-04 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Furr's-Wyatt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Furr's CEO Looking to Become Cafeteria King</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Michael Levenson, the cafeteria is an
all-American standby that occupies a perfect, sturdy niche in the
often volatile restaurant industry.
   ``It's not a juicier hamburger, it's not a faster pizza. It's
not a fad,'' said Levenson, chairman and chief executive officer of
Furr's-Bishop's Cafeterias Inc. ``And it's a reliable stream of
cash flow.''
   The cash-rich, low-debt balance sheets of the cafeteria segment
drew Levenson to acquire Furr's-Bishop's and has made Dallas-based
Wyatt Cafeterias Inc. his acquisition target for the past two years.
   Levenson said Thursday he would not give his takeover attempts,
but refused to specify his plans if his latest overture is rejected.
   The closely-held Wyatt has revenues of about $190 million and
120 restaurants nationwide.
   After first offering to buy the company in May 1986, Levenson
made several bids for Wyatt. Last Wednesday, he sweetened his offer
for Wyatt to $188.1 million in cash and securities from an earlier
$179.3 million bid.
   The latest $91.25 per-share bid came after Wyatt rejected
Levenson's $87 per-share cash offer in favor of one from a Wyatt
management-based employee stock ownership plan that bid $84 per
share.
   Wyatt shareholders are scheduled to vote on the ESOP offer Sept.
6, and Wyatt management has not yet responded to the latest
Furr's-Bishop's offer, Levenson said.
   ``If we don't get the Wyatt's deal that doesn't mean we're out
of the business of buying cafeterias,'' said Levenson, who owns a
small stake in Wyatt. ``We're going to grow this company.''
   The cafeteria business captured the 38-year-old Levenson's
attention after he bid unsuccessfully on companies such as
Midland-based Texas American Energy, Aloha Airlines of Hawaii and
Tesoro Petroleum Corp. of San Antonio.
   ``When I began studying the restaurant industry, the cafeteria
segment of the restaurant industry stood out with some real unique
features,'' he said.
   Convinced he had discovered a gold mine, in 1987 he acquired
Furr's Cafeterias and Bishop Buffets, based in Cedar Rapids, Iowa,
from K mart Corp for $237.5 million.
   He converted Furr's-Bishop's into a limited partnership, got it
listed on the New York Stock Exchange and sold 11 million
partnership units at $10 apiece. The partnership has promised to
pay a cash distribution of $1.30 a share this year.
   Furr's-Bishops is the nation's second largest operator of
cafeterias in the nation, with 126 operating under the Furr's name
in 10 states and 26 under the Bishop's name in seven states.
   He never earned a college degree, but Levenson became the
president of a family-owned bank in Carlsbad, N.M., before being
lured away by the burgeoning oil and gas industry.
   ``Just being able to walk along and pick up the crumbs the
Exxons of the world dropped and left would make you rich beyond
your wildest dreams,'' he said.
   After buying and selling oil and gas leases during the late
1970s, his attention was drawn to the takeover attempts within the
oil and gas industry by fellow West Texan T. Boone Pickens Jr. of
Amarillo.
   Levenson said his unsuccessful takeover runs at companies helped
establish his credibility in the New York financial community,
enabling him to consummate the deal for Furr's-Bishop's.
   For the second quarter this year, the cafeteria company posted
revenue of $70.9 million, a more than 6 percent increase over the
same quarter of 1987. Furr's-Bishop's had earnings of $2 million,
or 12 cents per share, the partnership's first quarter in the black.
   Levenson predicts the company's revenue will total $273 million
this year and that will post a profit.
   He is confident he's in the right business, and cites the
cafeteria business's lack of foriegn competition and relative
isolation from costly high-tech development.
   ``Cafeteria companies have survived the Great Depression, they
survived World War II, they survived the oil crunch and every boom
and bust in the agriculture market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
